<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / UK Company News: BSG increases to Pounds 12m and plans
Pounds 31m rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BSG INTERNATIONAL, the motor components, vehicle distribution, childcare
products and aircraft interior equipment group, announced an 8 per cent
increase in profits for 1992 together with a 1-for-4 rights issue to raise
Pounds 31.4m to fund planned capital investment.
The pre-tax outcome was Pounds 12m, compared with Pounds 11.1m, helped by a
strong performance from its Australian component plants, healthy demand in
Germany and a recovery in its car leasing and Birmingham dealer operations
following rationalisation.
The rights issue, underwritten by Morgan Grenfell and brokered by Panmure
Gordon, is priced at 62p, a discount of 19.5 per cent to the overnight
market price of 77p.
Yesterday the shares closed at 70p.
The fund-raising comes against the background of capital spending plans for
1993 and 1994 of Pounds 34m.
Of this Pounds 12m will be spent on a mirror plant in the US and Pounds 7m
on a Vauxhall dealership in Manchester and the relocation of a Ford
dealership in Cheltenham.
Without a rights issue to fund expansion, 'gearing would have got out of
hand; we needed it for future growth,' said Mr Tom Cannon, managing
director. Gearing at the end of 1992 was 49 per cent. Proceeds of the rights
issue would have cut it at that time to 13.7 per cent.
Both BSG's capital expenditure and its research and development spending
have been sustained through the recession. R&amp;D costs, charged against
trading profits, will be no less this year than the Pounds 8.9m spent in
1992.
Turnover was Pounds 555.1m, down from Pounds 569.8m, reflecting
deterioration in trading in the final quarter, especially in the UK.
However, so far this year there has been a slight imrpovement in orders
across all sectors of the business, although Mr Cannon observed that
problems with margins remained at LA Rumbold, the aircraft interiors
company.
The final dividend is 2.5p, maintaining the total at 3.2p.
Although covered by earnings per share of 3.46p, against 3.32p, part of the
cost will come from reserves following discontinued business charges of
Pounds 1.9m taken below the line.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>BSG International.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3714 Motor Vehicle Parts and Accessories.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
