<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Only two bids received for 30% Greencore
stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE IRISH government said last night that it had received only two bids for
its 30.4 per cent stake in Greencore, the sugar, milling and malting group.
One bid was from Archer-Daniels-Midland, a US agribusiness conglomerate, and
the other from Irish Life, a Dublin-based insurance concern.
No details were given of the price of the bids, but the government said that
ADM had 'reaffirmed its interest' in purchasing a stake providing that 'its
participation must exceed 25 per cent on a fully diluted basis'.
The Irish Life bid is to purchase just 2m shares of the 25.4m on offer,
'conditional on the government selling at least 20m shares to purchasers
including Irish Life'. Irish Life said last night that it was not acting on
behalf of any other investors to purchase the outstanding amount.
Earlier this month, the Irish agriculture minister Mr Joe Walsh said that
ADM had made an offer of 260p per share. Since then Greencore's shares have
risen to 270p. Mr Walsh said this week that the sale would not automatically
go to the highest bidder.
Mr Bertie Ahern, the finance minister, said that the criteria to be used in
assessing the government's decision would be 'price, the strategic
development of the company and the development of the food sector in
Ireland'.
The government has been under pressure from trade unions and the Labour
partners in the coalition to prevent the selling of the stake to a foreign
company. However, the fact that no Irish food company has made a bid for
Greencore and that Irish Life has only bid for less than 10 per cent of the
shares on offer, is something of an embarrassment to the government.
It must now decide whether to accept the joint ADM-Irish Life offers, which
are not incompatible, or to abandon the sale altogether.
</TEXT>
