<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Daimler discloses DM4bn of reserves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DAIMLER-Benz, Germany's larg-est industrial company, yesterday disclosed
'hidden reserves' of about DM4bn (Pounds 1.66bn) while announcing its plan
to obtain a share listing on the New York stock exchange.
Daimler will become the first German company to obtain a listing on the
exchange and is likely to lead the way for others as they attempt to
strengthen their ability to raise capital.
The company said yesterday that it had reached a compromise with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, the US regulatory body for securities
markets, which would allow it to list its shares on Wall Street this year.
The compromise would include the German company giving increased financial
details to meet US investors' expectations, Daimler said. The refusal of the
SEC and German groups to compromise on disclosure rules has for long been an
obstacle to the companies gaining access to the world's biggest capital
market.
Daimler said that it would change its accounting for the 1992 financial
year. This would disclose extraordinary profits of about DM4bn, more than
twice the expected net profits of between DM1.4bn and DM1.5bn. The profit in
1991 was DM1.9bn.
A Daimler-Benz listing would boost the New York Stock Exchange, which faces
increasing competition for business from electronic, regional and
international exchanges, notably London. The NYSE exchange has been trying
to promote itself as the leading international stock market, but the SEC's
strict disclosure rules have discouraged some large foreign companies from
listing in the US.
Mr Richard Breeden, chairman of the SEC, said yesterday that there had been
give on both sides and he thought the result would be a ' win-win' for the
two parties.
Mr William Donaldson, chairman of the NYSE, who has long campaigned for a
relaxation of SEC rules on foreign companies, said Daimler's announcement
stemmed from a 'breakthrough compromise that we have sought for a long
time.'
Daimler is undergoing a restructuring at Mercedes-Benz, its core car
subsidiary. It planned to hold a DM2bn rights issue last autumn but this was
postponed because of poor conditions on the German stock market.
</TEXT>
