<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Drug stocks fall on Merck warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DRUG stocks on both sides of the Atlantic tumbled yesterday after Merck &amp;
Co, the sector's biggest company, warned that earnings growth this year
would be slower than expected.
The US group also revealed its first-ever job reduction programme when it
announced 1,000 of its 38,000 employees would be made redundant this year.
Yesterday Merck's shares fell Dollars 2 1/4 to close at Dollars 32 3/4 . In
London, Glaxo Holdings closed down 17p to 597p in spite of news that its
migraine treatment Imigran had been given technical approval in France.
Merck blamed the slowdown on increasing competition in the US and healthcare
cost-containment measures worldwide. It also cited currency movements. The
announcement followed last week's similar warnings from Eli Lilly and Marion
Merrell Dow, the US drug groups.
The group said the effects would be seen in the first-quarter results and
would be particularly noticeable in the first half. Analysts downgraded
earnings growth predictions for Merck during 1993 from as high as 16 per
cent to about 10 per cent.
Merck has been hit both by its undertaking not to increase prices by more
than inflation and the growing ability of bulk healthcare providers to
negotiate drugs discounts. Sales have also been affected by health reforms
in Germany.
In the US, the price of some drugs are falling due to the growing power of
bulk healthcare providers called health management organisations (HMOs).
These account for about half of the US market. 'The drugs groups have dug
their own grave,' explained Mr Hermant Shah, pharmaceuticals analyst at HKS
&amp; Co in New York. 'They have been launching more medicines with little
additional therapeutic benefit. That has allowed the HMOs to trade one drug
off against another, driving down prices,' he said.
Lex, Page 22; World stock markets, Page 37; London SE, Back Page
