FT  24 MAR 93 / Timex union issues warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL leaders of the Amalgamated Engineering and Electrical Union
yesterday warned extremists not to interfere in the dispute at the Timex
factory in Dundee, following violence outside the circuit-board plant that
led to 16 arrests on Monday.
'Our message to outsiders is keep out and mind your own business,' said Mr
Gavin Laird, the union's general secretary. 'They are exacerbating the
dispute and making it more difficult to resolve the problem and save the
jobs of our members.'
None of the demonstrators who were arrested on Monday belongs to the union
or works at Timex, the US-owned multinational.
Mr Bill Jordan, the AEEU's president, added: 'An extreme reaction by an
employer has attracted extremists who are not part of our union. We want to
find a negotiated settlement and we reject the development that has take
place. Our members have obeyed the law.'
The strike - now in its fifth week - was sparked by the dismissal of all the
Timex manual workers by the company after a number of them, who had been in
dispute for 21 days over proposals for cuts in benefits, a pay freeze and
job cuts, had agreed to go back to work under protest. A substitute
workforce is being hired.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, also condemned the demonstrators. He said
during question time that 'rent-a-picket' was back, and this was 'not in the
interest of workers at Timex'. He said strikers 'had always faced the risk
of being sacked without the right to claim unfair dismissal'.
Editorial comment, Page 21
