<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Leading Article: Troubled times at Timex
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
VIOLENCE ON the picket line at Timex, and a rash of strikes and strike
threats on the railways, in the coal industry and at Ford, smack of an
old-fashioned bout of British labour militancy.
Appearances, however, are deceptive. All of these actions are defensive,
about job security rather than pay, and all, apart from Timex, are limited
in duration, designed primarily to provide a focal point for media
campaigns. Elsewhere there is no sign of a general pick-up in strike action.
Indeed, at a time of very high unemployment, employers are finding it
increasingly easy to push through pay freezes, especially in manufacturing.
Nevertheless, the Timex dispute does raise some questions about Britain's
labour laws. The conflict has little to do with the employment legislation
of the 1980s, except for the question of how far a trade union can support
its members in a dispute without exposing itself to legal attack. But it
does show that the law can be clumsy, and possibly unhelpful to both sides,
when dealing with the changes to employees' pay and conditions increasingly
demanded by competitive product markets.
The Timex dispute was originally about lay-offs. The company wanted to shed
a group of workers. The workforce suggested laying off different groups in
rotation and struck to support that position. The workers eventually decided
to return to work but refused to accept the less favourable terms and
conditions which the company had meanwhile decided to impose. The company
therefore sacked the whole workforce, including those who had worked through
the original dispute.
This story illustrates two facts of British labour law. First, it is often
difficult for employers to change an employment contract without consent,
even when they have good grounds. Second, since British workers have no
right to strike, employees can be sacked for breach of contract even if a
proper ballot has taken place. The result is that employers can be tempted
to use strikes about one problem to sort out another.
Timex said it was forced to sack its employees in order to change their
contracts of employment; otherwise each individual could have taken it to
court. Employers can give notice of termination of existing contracts and
provide new ones, but anyone not accepting the new contract can claim unfair
dismissal. In defending itself against such claims, the company would have
to show that the changes were necessary and that they were fairly
introduced.
It is in the interests of employers and trade unions that the framework of
employment contract law should be as clear as possible and that everyone
should respect lawfully agreed contracts. Labour law reformers should focus
on this objective.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Timex Electronics Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
