<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Brokers hit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The withdrawal from the London non-life reinsurance market of NRG, the Dutch
insurance group, triggered a late flurry of selling pressure in the two
leading insurance brokers, Sedgwick and Willis Corroon, which could be hit
by the contraction of the London market. Willis shares fell 5 to 198p on
turnover of 1m and Sedgwick 4 to 174p on 605,000 traded.
NRG's UK reinsurance arm, Victory, has a big chunk of London's reinsurance
market. And there were suggestions that another of the big reinsurance
groups may soon pull out of London. Prudential said yesterday that its
reinsurance subsidiary is chopping its reinsurance business by 50 per cent
this year. 'This will translate into premium rate increases, which should be
good for the composites,' said one analyst. 'But is could make life
increasingly difficult for the brokers,' he added. In the composites Royal
Insurance jumped 11 to 318p. Sun Alliance, however, dropped 6 to 346p after
one securities house was said to have adopted a cautious stance.
Prudential's preliminary results showed profits at the lower end of
expectations but the dividend was a touch better than most forecasts,
dealers said. Prudential shares moved up 3 to 329p.
Clyde Petroleum's Pounds 34m rights issue, a one-four at 44p, surprised the
market but caused little disruption to the Clyde share price which drifted 4
to 51p. The oil team at Hoare Govett, broker to Clyde and underwriter of the
rights issue, commented 'The development of Gryphon and adoption of
successful efforts accounting underpins future profits growth and a
sustainable and progressive dividend.' Lasmo attracted more keen buying in
front of this morning's preliminary numbers although many expect them to
include a reduction in the final dividend, possibly to 3p.
Glaxo returned to favour, the shares climbing 13 to 614p on 4.8m traded.
Dealers noted good US support for the shares ahead of the start of clinical
trials for the group's 3TC anti-aids drug. Wellcome rose 12 to 910p. Unichem
put on 7 1/2 to 243 1/2 p following the 49 per cent increase in profits.
Wolseley, the building materials group, raced up to 617p immediately
following the much better than expected figures before coming off the top
and closing a net 10 higher at 604p. A block of 3m shares was sold into the
market at 599p and mostly placed at 600p.
Bargain hunters helped engineering group Siebe shrug off recent weakness to
advance 5 to 460p. The market was unimpressed by a Pounds 126m rights issue
from components group BBA and the shares fell 7 to 170p, in response. Weir
Group were wanted ahead of today's figures and put on 4 to 648p. Also in
demand was James Wilkes, which added another 2 to 72p, on continued bid
speculation.
A two way pull was seen in P&amp;O, which reported figures in line with
expectations, and the sale of the Sutcliffe catering group to Granada Group.
Having jumped 26 to 627p, on the release of the figures, closer examination
of them saw the shares come off the top to close a net 2 better at 603p,
with turnover reaching 4.6m. Mr Steve Clapham at Credit Lyonnais Laing
appreciated the figures but reduced his current year forecast by Pounds 15m
to Pounds 295m to take account of the Sutcliffe disposal and higher than
expected net debt figure.
Results from Iceland Frozen Foods came in line with expectations. Most
analysts kept next year forecasts in the Pounds 66-69m range. The shares
advanced 9 to 744p. However, one foods specialist warned that the stock's
rating was looking high. J Sainsbury slipped 8 to 507p, Kwik Save 14 to 801p
and Argyll Group 10 to 343p.
Budget changes to FT statistics
The Financial Times will implement with effect from April 5th the Budget
reduction in the income tax rate applied to dividends to 20 per cent from 25
per cent. This will affect gross dividend yields shown for individual
companies in the London Share Service, and those calculated for the FT-SE
Actuaries UK Share Indices and the FT-Actuaries World Indices.
</TEXT>
