<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Berisford talks to Clark over bid: Board of shoe company yet
to decide as commodities group renegotiates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BERISFORD International, the property and commodities group, yesterday met
the board of C&amp;J Clark to renegotiate elements of its Pounds 160m-plus bid
for the family owned shoe manufacturer.
Observers were speculating that the Berisford bid, the highest by a small
margin, could well have won favour a majority of the board.
The property and commodities group is thought to be renegotiating some of
the conditions of its offer. These include exclusive rights of due diligence
and an indemnity for costs if a majority of the board agreed to recommend
Berisford, but shareholders rejected the bid.
Clark yesterday said it had not decided on which of three bidders to
recommend and it planned to meet again on Friday. An announcement would be
made after shareholders had been informed. However, insiders said a majority
of the directors had decided, although a final attempt at reaching a
unanimous decision would be made this week.
At least four members of the 11-strong board have objected to a sale to any
of the bidders: Berisford, Fii the shoe manufacturer and a consortium of
existing shareholders backed by Electra Investment Trust. There is a fourth
institutional bidder which has been rejected.
If Berisford's offer wins approval, shareholders should expect that Clark
will be one of four divisions in the international holding company which Mr
Alan Bowkett, chairman of Berisford, intends to build.
Cost-cutting is likely to be a priority although - like all the bidders -
Berisford says it is committed to UK manufacturing.
Berisford intends to chase volume overseas, with opportunities in the
children's market. The Clark brand, Mr Bowkett believes, has languished for
too long as a mainly British product.
Berisford intends to keep the struggling retail division, but reposition the
products. Emphasis on fashion and keeping up with trend changes are key
elements of Berisford's strategy.
The other bidders, by contrast, aimed to make Clark their main business. Fii
would, in fact, treble its size if it succeeded in a bid for Clark. The
company is believed to have stressed to the board the opportunities
presented by combining its fashion-oriented range with Clark's children's
and casual shoe expertise.
It planned to introduce a high quality range of children's and casual shoes
to its main customer Marks &amp; Spencer.
Fii also sought to stress its commitment to UK manufacturing, and has said
its bid would not mean significant job losses.
The consortium, meanwhile, has made a bid in which existing shareholders
would be offered a 49 per cent stake in the business.
The new vehicle will back current management strategy, although under a new
leader. It would pursue 'global economies of scale' such as increasing the
investment in brand promotion, both at home and abroad.
Reebok for example, has been reported to spend some Pounds 190m a year on
advertising, while Clark spends a mere Pounds 5m. Yet Reebok is only twice
the size of Clark.
The emphasis would be on the group's strength in the children's and men's
shoe market. The final goal of the institutions is a flotation in five
years.
However the board decides between these options, it is difficult to escape
one basic fact: the very public row which has rocked this intensely private
Quaker company for the past seven months is unlikely to disappear when the
board finally announces its decision.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Berisford International.
    C and J Clark.
    FII Group.
    Electra Investment Trust.
</CO>
<XX>
