<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / TUC condemns cost of closures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CLOSING each of the 31 threatened pits will cost between Pounds 8m to Pounds
10m more for each pit than keeping it open, says an assessment released
yesterday by the Trades Union Congress.
The TUC said its study showed that the total net costs of pit closures,
after taking into account unemployment benefit and tax losses, would be
Pounds 80m for the 10 pits earmarked for early closure and Pounds 320m for
all 31 pits.
The TUC called for immediate government action to 'create a larger market
for coal as recommended by the Commons trade and industry select committee'.
The committee called for measures widely interpreted as meaning expansion of
the coal market by at least 16m tonnes a year.
The government's white paper is likely to lead to considerably less
expansion.
The TUC study challenged the government's assertions that the costs of pit
closures would be short-lived and that saving pits would have a severe
impact on jobs elsewhere. It argued that the net additional costs of closing
pits would damage industry's competitiveness.
Mr Norman Willis, TUC general secretary, said closing pits made no economic
sense. The public should be told how much more it would cost to close pits
than to keep them open, he said.
Pit Closures: The costs to the Taxpayer. TUC, Congress House, Great Russell
Street, London WC1B 3LS.
</TEXT>
