<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / International Company News: Hudson's Bay takes over Canadian
retailing rival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HUDSON'S BAY, Canada's biggest department store group, is taking over
troubled Woodward's, the oldest name in western Canada retailing. The deal
is estimated to be worth nearly CDollars 100m (USDollars 80.3m).
The Bay intends to turn some of Woodward's best store sites into Bay and
Zellers units. Bay's national market share will rise from 22 per cent to
almost 25 per cent.
'We will buy Woodward's shares and gain all its assets, including
accumulated tax losses,' said Mr Gary Lukassen, the Bay's executive
vice-president for finance.
The Toronto-based retailer, now 25 per cent owned by the Kennes Thomson
family, will dramatically raise its market share in western Canada and gain
valuable properties.
Woodward's had filed for court protection after heavy losses and mounting
debts. It had closed its Vancouver flagship store and laid off 1,500
employees.
In the nine months ended December 31 last, the company lost CDollars 80.6m
on revenues of CDollars 245m.
</TEXT>
