<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Plans to mothball mines expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, PHILIP STEPHENS and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR met more than half the cabinet last night to finalise details
of the government's proposed lifeline for coal mines threatened with
closure.
The cabinet committee discussed a draft white paper, which sets out in broad
terms how the coal market could be expanded, and aims to avert a threatened
revolt by Tory MPs.
The government, which is understood to believe that around a dozen of the 31
threatened pits could be kept open at least in the short term, is also
believed to have drawn up plans to mothball indefinitely up to six others.
The aim is to reassure Tory critics that reserves of deep-mined coal would
not necessarily be wasted.
The mothballed pits would be open to bids from the private sector once
legislation to privatise the industry was passed by the Commons.
The plans centre on a limited Treasury subsidy to make UK coal more
competitive, but this may last only a year or two, while the privatisation
of British Coal would be speeded up.
Treasury ministers have resisted offering a subsidy above about Pounds 500m.
The paper is likely to be published tomorrow after formal approval by the
full cabinet. Downing Street indicated that Mr Major may press ahead with
the white paper plans before publication even if core contracts are not
formally agreed between British Coal and the electricity generators.
Publication will be followed by an intensive campaign to win over waverers
on the Tory back benches.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, would face pressure to
resign if the package failed to win the support of MPs.
Intensive energy users are hoping the white paper will encourage moves
enabling them to bypass the electricity wholesale pool and reduce their
electricity bills.
On Monday the British Management Data Association, an independent
organisation backed by 25 companies, presented a proposal to ministers that
the association says would provide British Coal with more security.
Under the proposal large companies including Imperial Chemical Industries,
would sign long-term deals with generators for coal-fired electricity.
Analysts were sceptical yesterday about whether the scheme would increase
demand for coal.
Meanwhile PowerGen said it had signed an eight-year deal with Electricite de
France to supply electricity. Analysts believe it could help save one of the
threatened pits.
</TEXT>
