<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / World Trade News: Tough talk on Nafta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SIDE agreements it is proposed to attach to the North American Free
Trade Agreement must raise wages and clean up the environment on both sides
of the US-Mexican border, President Bill Clinton said yesterday.
Referring to Nafta in language generally used by its opponents, he
acknowledged that the pact was 'not simply a trade agreement, this is also
an investment agreement'. Because it would make Mexico a 'much more
attractive' investment, the Bush administration had negotiated rules
protecting intellectual property and investment. 'Shouldn't we also, in the
interest of both the economies of Mexico and the US, see that basic
environmental standards and labour standards are observed?' he said.
</TEXT>
