<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Spanish socialists reel from a body blow: Finance
allegations by tax inspectors embarrass the party as election looms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SPAIN'S RULING socialist party was yesterday struggling to ride a political
body blow, after Spanish tax inspectors confirmed reports that the party had
systematically financed itself illegally in the late 1980s by selling
phantom consulting services to big business.
The revelations come as polls show the socialists already slipping badly
ahead of a general election later this year.
They are suffering the effects of a deepening recession and the knock-on
effect of last weekend's Socialist defeat in France.
Legal confirmation of illicit financing, after two years of vehement denials
by the party leadership, has renewed opposition hopes that corruption will
become a decisive issue ahead of the election.
The inspectors, on secondment from the Finance Ministry to a judge
investigating socialist party financing, said late on Monday that consulting
companies operated by senior party officials had taken receipts of some
Pta1bn (Pounds 5.75m) from some of Spain's largest banks and industrial
companies between 1987 and 1990.
For the past two years, newspapers have been alleging that these companies -
including Banco Central, Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, Asea Brown Boveri's Spanish
subsidiary, Catalana de Gas and the Pryca supermarket chain - paid money to
two companies in return for expensive reports on their sectors of business.
Hardly any of the companies have since been able to produce reports for
which they paid, on occasion, more than Pta100m, some saying they have been
lost.
The inspectors implied that those reports which had been produced had been
hastily cobbled together by the business clients.
They said these clients owed about Pta437m in unpaid taxes.
The 'consulting' companies involved, Filesa and Time Export, were controlled
by Mr Carlos Navarro, the former treasurer of the socialist parliamentary
party, and Mr Josep Maria Sala, administrative secretary of the Catalan
socialist party and a member of the party's national executive.
The two men, said the inspectors, excercised 'active de jure and/or de facto
ownership and management' of the companies.
Money taken from business 'clients' was then used to pay socialist election
expenses and, to disguise that, they took receipts not from party suppliers
but from companies run by Ms Aida Alvarez, the socialist party's national
financial co-ordinator until 1986.
The socialist party said yesterday that it would not try to protect the
parliamentary immunity of anyone implicated in the scandal, but it is not
clear whether the investigating judge, Mr Marino Barbero, will now begin
trial proceedings.
If he does so before an election, the political cost to the socialists could
be huge.
The Filesa report is embarrassing for Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez, who
has sharply criticised Judge Barbero for making searches of party
headquarters in Madrid, implying that the probe is politically motivated.
The report marks probably the lowest point socialist fortunes have reached
since the last election in 1989.
Mr Gonzalez is likely to try to regain some political ground in a state of
the nation address next month in which he is widely expected to announce an
anti-corruption drive.
With polls now showing the socialists level-pegging with the conservative
opposition, the Partido Popular, it is far from certain, though, that he has
not already lost too much momentum.
</TEXT>
