<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Russia in Crisis: Navy admits dumping nuclear reactors at
sea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA has admitted the Soviet navy sank nuclear submarines and radioactive
materials in its northern seas.
An official report seen by the Financial Times paints a chilling picture of
secret pollution which began in 1959. The report, drawing on KGB and
military documents declassified on the orders of President Boris Yeltsin,
was drawn up after a ship from Greenpeace, the environmentalist
organisation, was seized by the Russian navy for trying to measure the
radioactivity last October.
Between 1959 and 1992, 18 reactors from nuclear submarines were dumped at
sea after accidents or decommissioning, as well as a reactor from the
nuclear-powered ice-breaker Lenin which was simply put on to a barge and
sunk. Seven of the reactors, complete with their submarines and dangerous
nuclear fuel, were dumped into the northern Kara and Barents seas after
on-board accidents made them too dangerous to handle.
The report says that 2.3m curies of radioactive material - 50m curies was
released by the world's worst nuclear accident, at Chernobyl - was dumped
into the sea over this period. It specifies where and when the dumping was
carried out.
But Professor Alexei Yablokov, the presidential adviser who led the
commission which produced the report, said research was now needed to
determine the harm done to the environment and draw up steps to repair the
damage.
'We don't know the extent of the danger because there is no data on what
radioactivity seeped into the ecosystem. Maybe nothing terrible happened.
But maybe it did get into fish and will then go on to human beings.'
Mr Yeltsin has ordered the government to draw up a programme to deal with
the issue. He has also instructed Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the foreign minister,
to circulate the report among the international community.
Greenpeace has urged the Group of Seven industrialised companies to consider
urgent assistance for Russia to deal with what it describes as the Russian
navy's 'deadly cold war legacy'.
Russian nuclear submarines are continuing to dump liquid radioactive waste
at sea for lack of on-shore storage and reprocessing facilities. Britain,
France and the US, the other countries to operating nuclear submarines, as a
rule return the waste back to land.
Despite signing in 1976 the London Convention banning disposal of highly
radioactive materials at sea the Soviet Union ignored the ban.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9711 National Security.
</IN>
