<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / World News in Brief: Yugoslav peace talks in peril as
Karadzic leaves
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Yugoslav peace talks in New York appeared in doubt last night as Radovan
Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, withdrew and prepared to fly home. Lord
Owen, one of the two international mediators, said Mr Karadzic refused to
sign the proposed map dividing Bosnia. The UN Security Council again put off
voting on a plan to enforce a no-fly zone over Bosnia. The delay was caused
by Russian efforts to restrain the proposed action, mainly aimed against the
Serbs.
A UN airlift to evacuate wounded Moslems from the besieged Bosnian town of
Srebrenica was due to begin early today, carried out by British and French
helicopters. The commander of UN peacekeeping troops in Bosnia, General
Philippe Morillon, said he had reached agreement with Moslems to evacuate
Serb families from the Moslem city of Tuzla.
Meanwhile, Austria, host to 60,000 refugees from Bosnia, said it would no
longer accept asylum-seekers from the region.
