<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Survey of Japanese Financial Markets (8): Complaining in
code - The early results of tougher lending criteria
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMALL COMPANIES in the UK and the US have complained bitterly about their
treatment at the hands of banks. In Japan the complaints may be more coded,
but they are just as heartfelt.
Bad loan books, weak balance sheets and a declining capital base have forced
Japan's commercial banks to tighten up their lending criteria - perhaps even
more so than their western counterparts. At the same time the slump in stock
prices has cut off access to equity capital for most companies. And much of
the equity warrant related finance raised in the heyday of the boom economy
is due to be repaid in the next 18 months.
A great deal has been made of the tidal wave of some Y10,000bn of
warrant-backed paper which companies will have to refinance in 1993, but it
would appear to be the least serious of the problems.
Most of the money was raised by large blue chip companies which either do
not need to replace the borrowings because of falling capital expenditure,
or have little difficulty raising money from banks, insurance companies or
the bond market. According to Ms Mineko Sasaki-Smith of Credit Suisse Japan,
some 70 per cent of this year's capital requirement may already have been
financed through straight bond issues.
As short term interest rates have fallen, bonds have become a more
attractive investment for many institutions, so blue chip companies have
found a ready market. And while the dividends of 5-6 per cent which
companies are having to pay on new bond issues are well above the near-zero
cost of capital of the bubble economy years, the higher interest bill is
only a modest drain on corporate cashflows.
Because banks and insurance companies are now more cautious, but still need
to book assets, competition to lend to high quality companies is, if
anything, more intense than it was in the 1980s.
Mr Hideya Kubo of Nippon Life highlights the dilemma: 'We are keen to expand
our lending to quality companies, but it is very hard at present because so
few companies want to borrow. With a significant rise in the stockmarket
unlikely, and yields on shares too low, we have been forced to hold a lot of
domestic bonds. And now that yields on these have fallen too, we may have to
consider more overseas bonds as well.'
Nippon Life is also trying to establish more regional relationships in Japan
so that it can increase its lending to large regional companies outside the
Tokyo area. 'We have established contacts with over 400 new companies in the
last year,' says Mr Kubo.
Still, even if large companies can get the limited finance they need as they
struggle to strengthen their balance sheets, small companies face a harder
time. In February the Japanese ministry of finance publicly called on the
banks to make more loans to small companies: a tacit admission that there is
a credit crunch in some sectors at least. This contradicts the banks'
argument that they have only returned to pre-bubble criteria for assessing
loans, and that they have not become overly conservative.
Mr Yasuo Noda, managing director of Dai-Ichi Kango Bank, puts the case: 'It
is true that growth in lending is low, but that partly reflects borrowers
balance sheet needs. Demand for loans is falling too. We can earn a higher
spread from lending to small firms so we do want to lend to good small
companies.'
The difficulty comes in judging what is a creditworthy small business. Mr
Noda acknowledges that while bank managers are under instructions not to
overreact, there may be a natural tendency to become over-cautious when so
much lending has gone bad in recent years.
And Mr Kenji Mitzutani, the senior managing director at Tokai bank, admits
that 'small companies may find it more difficult to get further loans,
particularly if they want to use property as collateral.'
The property issue is important because in many cases it is the only
security small businesses can offer. Prices of residential land have fallen
by about a third, but there are no reliable figures for commercial property
because the market has simply dried up. Some analysts think that the
property market may fall by another quarter before it hits bottom.
Difficulty in valuing any collateral on offer is one more reason for banks
to be nervous. Many companies, even quite small ones, have made life harder
for themselves by speculating in the boom years and coming to grief.
For example, Yanmar, an agricultural tools manufacturer, has a finance
subsidiary with substantial debts. It may have to sell the land on which its
headquarters stands, simply to repair its balance sheet - something no
Japanese company would normally consider.
If bank finance is hard to come by, equity is almost impossible to raise. In
Nagoya - Japan's third city, located right in the centre of its
manufacturing heartland - there is a queue of medium sized companies just
waiting to get a listing on the local stock exchange.
Mr Ichiro Kawai, president of the Nagoya Stock Exchange (NSE), says: 'It has
been harder and harder to get a listing for small and medium sized companies
on the NSE since the supplementary budget last August. I know of at least
seven companies which want a listing as soon as possible, but they will have
to wait at least until the next financial year which starts in April.'
There are plenty of companies behind them. Mr Kentaro Sakai, president of
the Nagoya-based Maruman Securities, thinks that over 30 companies would
like to come to the Nagoya market in the next year or so. But with little
money flowing into the equity market, getting such issues underwritten will
be tough. (The government has acknowledged as much, by pulling issues such
as the flotation of JR East railways and a further tranche of NTT stock,
despite the fact that it would help fund the expanding budget deficit.)
Though life is tough, there is at least a partial silver lining. With
official interest rates going down, many small firms have seen some fall in
their financing bills - even those whose banks have widened out their
lending margins. And in Japan there is still a culture of saving businesses
wherever possible, rather than grabbing the collateral and throwing the
company to the receiver.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6021 National Commercial Banks.
    P6311 Life Insurance.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Services.
    MKTS  Market data.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
