<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / ITV output worries few in poll on violence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RESULTS of an Independent Television Commission survey of attitudes to
commercial network television indicate that people are not increasingly
taking offence at the amount of sex, bad language and violence on
television.
The survey questioned 1,239 people aged 16 and over and was conducted last
year as part of the commission's statutory obligations.
Seventy per cent said they found nothing offensive on commercial network
television. That compares with 72 per cent in 1991, 70 per cent in 1990 and
65 per cent in 1989.
Nothing offensive was found on BBC1 by 74 per cent (75 per cent in 1991);
BBC2 scored 80 per cent (the same as 1991); and Channel 4 registered 72 per
cent (73 per cent in 1991).
Among cable and satellite TV viewers - surveyed for the first time - 93 per
cent were not offended by satellite film channels. Of the 1,603 people asked
about cable and satellite TV, only 4 per cent cited violence as a source of
offence.
Television: the Public's View. Published by John Libbey, 13 Smiths Yard,
Summerley Street, London SW18 4HR. Pounds 16.
</TEXT>
