<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Watchdog warns MoD on sale of surplus arms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Ministry of Defence is preparing for a 'dramatic' sell-off of military
equipment without an adequate grasp of sales and pricing techniques, the
National Audit Office warns today.
Items on offer over the next two years may include obsolete Phantom and
Buccaneer aircraft, Leander frigates and Oberon submarines. The audit
office, the government spending watchdog, says sales will be 'on a scale
unprecedented since the period following the second world war'.
It says smaller disposals over the past five years have raised almost Pounds
200m, but that more could have been realised. The value of some ships, for
example, was reduced unnecessarily by the premature stripping out of
equipment.
The office adds that the Ministry of Defence needs to tighten safeguards
against fraud and theft in the light of 'a major investigation' by police at
its disposal depots.
The second-hand market is competitive because of defence cuts in many
countries, the audit office says. But the ministry has failed to assess the
identities, strategies and strengths of its competitors.
There has been progress in improving the efficiency of equipment sales, the
office says, and the ministry has created a directorate to centralise sales
of surplus equipment.
It has been involved in the sale of 35 ships to south America and south-east
Asia, as well as tank spares to Kuwait and ammunition to New Zealand, Chile
and Sri Lanka.
The number of aircraft sold more than trebled to 102 in 1991-92 compared
with a year before, and the ministry disposed successfully of several
hundred tonnes of time-expired ration-pack biscuits to zoos and
manufacturers of pet food.
Yet the directorate still relies largely on a manual database because its
computers have failed to work, says the audit office which blames 'funding
limitations and a lack of appreciation of the directorate's requirements'. A
shortage of management information means that 'the directorate has
insufficient information on prices achieved and costs incurred to know
whether they are covering their costs'.
The handling of auctions is also criticised by the audit office. It says
most buyers at the ministry's auctions are late in their payments, and urges
that professional houses should be consulted about producing a list of
possible changes to the ministry's auction procedures with the aim of
increasing the prices obtained.
The ministry said it was studying the report and hoped to make a response
within weeks.
Disposal by Sale of Defence Surplus Equipment and Stores. House of Commons
Paper 557. HMSO. Pounds 7.40.
</TEXT>
