<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / US backs British role in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD MORTIMER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN was urged to play 'a central and vigorous role' in Europe yesterday
by the US ambassador, Mr Raymond Seitz.
Such a role, Mr Seitz said, 'adds considerable value and weight' to the
Anglo-American relationship, the value of which 'is exponentially increased
or diminished by Britain's position in the multilateral Europe'.
But, he added, the US was also anxious 'that Britain preserve its capacity
for independent action', notably in the military field. On a wide range of
security issues after the cold war 'the willingness of either Washington or
London to respond. . . will depend in large measure on the willingness of
the other to act as well'.
He added: 'The overlap of our strategic interests may not be quite so
extensive as before'.
Mr Seitz, appointed by President George Bush as the first career diplomat to
hold the post, is thought likely to stay in London for at least another
year.
But the Clinton administration has yet to confirm this.
