<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Output by Bosch to leave Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOSCH, the German vehicle components, electronics and power tools group, is
to transfer production of car alternators from Stuttgart to south Wales and
Spain.
The company says alternator production will cease 'in the medium term' at
Feuerbach, Stuttgart. Production will be moved to a plant at Miskin, near
Cardiff, and a smaller factory at Treto in Spain 'in order to reduce costs
and thus secure competitiveness'. Bosch says a cut of up to 700 jobs at
Feuerbach, which will continue to make other components, 'cannot be
excluded'.
The Miskin plant, which has been manufacturing alternators since it opened
two years ago, is expected to double annual alternator production to 5m by
1995-96, and to increase its workforce over this period from 700 to 1,200.
Bosch said Feuerbach had been a pilot facility for a new compact alternator
and it had always been the company's strategy to transfer production to its
Welsh and Spanish plants.
The alternator made at Miskin, where the overall investment in the plant and
equipment is about Pounds 100m, is designed to cope with the increasing
amount of electrical components in cars. Eighty per cent of the Miskin
alternators are exported. A second production hall in Wales will be opened
later this year.
The arrival of Japanese car-makers in the UK was an important factor in
Bosch choosing to open Miskin, which also has lower labour and production
costs than Stuttgart. Bosch has a no-strike agreement at Miskin and says
that staff relations are very good.
</TEXT>
<XX>
