<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Extradition move soon in charity case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS, GILLIAN TETT and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH police are planning to press for the extradition from Belgium of Mr
Gamil Naguib, one of two men named in a High Court writ last month filed by
the Salvation Army alleging fraud of more than Pounds 6m.
The move came after details of Mr Naguib's whereabouts were passed to the
Metropolitan and City of London police fraud squad by The Independent
newspaper. Mr Naguib was found in Antwerp. He had been missing since the
writ was issued on February 15.
Formal extradition proceedings need to be processed through the Crown
Prosecution Service and the Home Office. Details of Mr Naguib have been
passed to Belgian and other European police forces through Interpol.
Police are confident that a second man named in the writ, Mr Stuard Ford,
will soon return to Britain voluntarily.
It emerged yesterday that the Crown Prosecution Service has been given
documents relating to discussions between individuals representing the
Salvation Army and an organisation claiming to belong to the United Nations.
It is understood discussions involved some of the individuals named in last
month's writ. The discussions were made on behalf of the ACP Investment and
Trade Bank, which has been disowned by the UN and was under investigation in
the US.
According to a bulletin from the US Controller of the Currency dated August
14 1992, ACP may have been operating a banking business in the US without
authorisation.
Dr Antoine Yameogo, ACP's executive co-ordinator, told the Financial Times
that his bank had received a UN mandate to operate for humanitarian and
development purposes in 1979 and in the early 1980s. UN officials said they
had never heard of the bank. Colonel Grenville Burn, who was in charge of
Salvation Army fundraising and involved in contacts between the charity and
Mr Naguib and Mr Ford, yesterday refused to comment.
</TEXT>
