<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Clarke to reduce size of police
authorities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMALLER and more businesslike police authorities will lead a drive for
better performance and value-for-money under proposals announced by Mr
Kenneth Clarke, home secretary, yesterday.
He told the Commons he planned to devolve responsibility within police
forces to 'local police units who will be directly accountable to their
local communities,' cutting out unnecessary headquarters and management
tiers.
But, under pressure from cabinet colleagues and chief constables, he is
moving cautiously on possible amalgamations between the 43 English and Welsh
forces. There will be no immediate mergers but Mr Clarke intends to simplify
statutory procedures 'to allow for amalgamations when the time is right'.
Yesterday's proposals form part of a review of the Pounds 6bn-a-year police
service aimed at improving its managerial and operational efficiency.
The next phase is due in May when a committee of inquiry into police
responsibilities and rewards under Sir Patrick Sheehy, chairman of BAT
industries, produces its report. This is likely to recommend a simplified
rank structure and performance-related pay.
Police authorities comprise two thirds local councillors and one third
magistrates. Mr Clarke envisages much smaller 16-strong bodies - eight
councillors, three magistrates, and five business people and others
appointed by the home secretary. The home secretary would appoint the
authority's chair from among the 16.
A police authority for London will be created. At present, the home
secretary is responsible for the Metropolitan Police.
Mr Clarke told the Commons that the funding structure, with central and
local government contributing to police costs, would continue in broadly the
same proportions as now.
The central government contribution would be cash-limited while the local
portion would be subjected to local government expenditure controls. But
police forces would have greater freedom to decide how to spend and manage
their resources.
Mr Clarke intends to set national objectives for the police service, while
police authorities will produce local performance targets. The results will
be published so that the public can compare forces' performance.
The proposals will be addressed in detail in a white paper in June, followed
by legislation. Mr Clarke's plans to reduce local authority representation
on police authorities, and add his own appointees, is likely to prove the
most controversial aspect of the package.
MPs gave a cautious welcome to the proposals, but Mr Clarke was warned from
both sides of the House not to follow a 'bigger is better' concept in
initiating amalgamations to reduce the duplication of headquarters and other
facilities.
Mr Clarke refused to be drawn about the likelihood of the City of London
force continuing as a separate entity, insisting that he had not begun to
consider the number of likely amalagamations.
He emphasised that the more powerful and businesslike police authorities
envisaged would be able to decide how to apportion their budgets between
expenditure on manpower and equipment.
Editorial Comment, Page 21
</TEXT>
<XX>
