<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Government grasps for treaty
life-support - As the bill to ratify the Maastricht treaty returns to the
House of Commons, FT writers look at the remaining obstacles to its passage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR Mr John Major it is life or death. If the deal he negotiated with his
European partners in the Dutch town of Maastricht in December 1991 fails to
win the endorsement of the British parliament his premiership will be
destroyed. Close colleagues of the prime minister are convinced he would
quit, along with Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary.
As the treaty heads for the final stage of its tortuous passage through the
House of Commons, the political stakes could not be higher. All the serious
betting is that the treaty - and Mr Major - will survive, and that by late
July, or at worst the autumn, Maastricht will be ratified. Britain will
again have held on to the coat - tails of Europe.
Even ardent opponents will admit privately that they believe the chances of
sinking the legislation are slim. On the central issue of principle -
whether Britain should ratify - there is a clear majority of the Commons in
favour. On a 'free vote' - unencumbered by the obligations of party
allegiance - around two thirds of the 650 MPs would support it.
But life for Mr Major is not that simple. The curious coincidence of
interest between 50 or so Conservative diehard opponents of the treaty and
the determination (they would say duty) of the opposition parties to weaken
the government at every opportunity conspires against him.
Between 25 and 30 Tory MPs have defied consistently powerful threats and
pleas for loyalty to vote against their own government. A further 20 to 25
abstain. Labour and the Liberal Democrats support the principle of the
treaty. But they want ratification on their terms and want in the process to
damage the government. Mr Major's paper majority of 20 MPs is thus rendered
worthless.
The government is hampered also by the arcane procedures of the House of
Commons - a set of rules for debate which allows opponents to support the
principle of a piece of legislation but to seriously delay and disrupt its
passage.
Between them the Euro - sceptics, the Labour, Liberal Democrat and smaller
opposition parties can dictate the timetable for the legislation. They can
filibuster. They can prevent, when they wish, the government winning the
votes it needs to speed up progress of the legislation with all - night and
weekend sittings.
More threateningly, the combined forces ranged against Mr Major can, if
their alliance holds, amend the legislation. They have already done so once
 -on a relatively minor issue. But if they were to find an amendment (and
they have not yet) to change the legislation in a way which forced the
government to embrace the social chapter then they just might derail the
whole process. Mr Major would not - could not - ratify a treaty without the
opt-out he negotiated from its social dimension.
The risk of an ambush - and of an unpredictable defeat - will remain until
the treaty passes its final House of Commons hurdle - the so - called third
reading.
On an optimistic timetable the third reading will come early in June. On a
pessimistic forecast it might not be before mid July. Then the legislation
will face loud opposition during a month or so in the House of Lords. Lady
Thatcher and Lord Tebbit, the self - appointed spokesman for the nation's
street - corner Europhobes, will lead the attack. But in the Lords, Mr Major
has a comfortable in - built majority. There will be plenty of noise but no
real threat to the substance of the legislation.
Mr Major cannot afford to be other than optimistic. The endless wrangling
has sapped the authority of his premiership. His is the first government
since the row over devolution which destroyed the Labour administration of
the late 1970s which has not been able to dictate the terms of debate for a
key piece of legislation. He depends on backroom deals with one or other of
the opposition parties. After 13 years with unchallengeable majorities, the
government has found it hard to rediscover the humility to strike such
bargains.
Ministers freely admit that until the treaty is ratified they will not be
able to regain a grip on domestic policy. Other European leaders may be
frustrated by the delay in ratification. None finds it more debilitating
than Mr Major.
That frustration is visible in the swings in the prime minister's mood. On
some occasions he acts as if determined to crush the enemy within. On others
he replaces scorn with attempts at persuasion. His own view of the treaty -
that it is vital to retain a British voice in the future of a wider Europe -
is distorted by his habit of focusing alternately on its positive elements
and then on the British opt - outs from monetary union and the social
chapter. 'Ratify it because it will never be implemented' sometimes seems to
be the message.
The struggle risks doing serious long - term damage to the Conservatives.
The declared dissidents have the private support of a similar number of more
discreet opponents. The risk is that it will prove impossible to heal the
schism.
There are problems too for the Labour and Liberal Democrat parties. Both
parade their pro - European credentials (though Labour has its own sizeable
hard core of passionate Eurosceptics). They are tarnishing those credentials
in their anxiety to weaken Mr Major. Political opportunism has a price.
But for now - and until the ratification documents leave the Palace of
Westminster to receive the signature of the Queen - Mr Major remains the
helpless victim of his negotiating triumph in Maastricht.
</TEXT>
