<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Row over move to halt toxic cargo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECHEM, the waste management group, yesterday said it was surprised and
disappointed by a request from Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, for
his German counterpart to prevent a shipment of waste being transported to
the UK.
Earlier this week, Mr Howard asked Mr Klaus Topfer to ban the export of
about 1,000 tonnes of hazardous waste from Hamburg to Rechem's incinerator
in Pontypool, Gwent.
'The government appears to be marking out the pitch and then redrawing the
lines during the match,' said Mr John Shaughnessy, external affairs manager
at Rechem.
'The waste involved is entirely consistent with the range of materials for
which we are licensed,' he added.
Rechem, a subsidiary of Shanks &amp; McEwan, the UK's largest waste management
group, said it had been in advanced negotiations with Boehringer Ingelheim,
owner of the waste. It added that no specialist capacity appeared to be
available in Germany.
The German group said it was negotiating with a number of companies in
Germany and other European countries to dispose of the waste.
