FT  24 MAR 93 / Energy users look for cut in costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTENSIVE energy users are hoping the white paper will encourage moves that
would enable them to bypass the electricity wholesale pool and to reduce
their electricity costs.
On Monday the British Management Data Association, an independent
organisation backed by 25 companies, presented a proposal to ministers that
the association says would provide British Coal with security.
Under the plan large companies, including Imperial Chemical Industries,
would sign long-term deals with generators for coal-fired electricity.
Analysts were sceptical yesterday about whether the scheme would increase
demand for coal.
Meanwhile PowerGen, the electricity generator, said it had signed an
eight-year deal to supply Electricite de France with power via the
cross-Channel electricity link.
The deal might lead to sales of more than Pounds 100m. Analysts believe it
could help save one of the threatened pits. Closing each threatened pit
would cost between Pounds 8m to Pounds 10m more per pit than keeping it
open, says an assessment released yesterday by the Trades Union Congress.
The TUC figures took into account extra unemployment benefit payments and
tax losses resulting from closures.
Its study challenged the government's assertions that the costs of pit
closures would be short-lived and that saving pits would have a severe
impact on jobs elsewhere.
