<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Hospital withdraws redundancy notices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ESSEX hospital has withdrawn redundancy notices to 160 employees, whose
jobs were being contracted out to the private sector, following revised
government guidelines on European Community legislation.
Goodmayes Hospital, which will become the Redbridge Hospital Trust on April
1, said it had been advised last year by the Department of Health that
Transfer of Undertakings Regulations (Protection of Employment), or Tupe,
would not apply to its contracting-out of domestic services for its new
hospital. Where they apply, staff must be retained on existing terms and
conditions.
Mr Colin Houghton, personnel director, said revised guidelines issued
earlier this month had caused him to seek legal advice and withdraw the
notices. Negotiations would take place with ISS Mediclean, which was to have
taken over the contract, to see if it still wanted to bid.
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, yesterday praised the
performance of NHS trusts as she confirmed that another 138 would become
operational from April 1. A total of 156 are now fully operational in
Britain, she said.
</TEXT>
