<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Minister offers BR talks on pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is offering to negotiate with British Rail's board of
directors over the future of BR's Pounds 8.5bn pension scheme after
privatisation.
However, it has not backed down from its initial proposals that would allow
it to take a portion of the scheme's assets in exchange for a promise to
increase pensions in line with inflation - the BR scheme's current policy.
Last week BR's directors privately told the government that proposals for
the pension schemes after privatisation were inadequate and needed
improvement. Specifically, the directors are seeking the right of BR
employees who transfer involuntarily to the private sector to remain members
of a joint industry scheme as long as they do not leave railway employment.
Yesterday Mr Roger Freeman, public transport minister, said: 'The government
does not rule out the possibility that the existing British Rail scheme
could remain open in the short term and the pensioners remain in it with
existing British Rail staff.'
The government contemplates that scheme members could then have five years'
grace until privatisation is completed. 'I do not at present see a need for
individuals to have a right to remain in the joint industry scheme. But we
will discuss this idea further with the trustees and others,' Mr Freeman
said.
The government had proposed that all current employees whose division is
privatised would be required to leave the BR scheme and join their new
employer's scheme.
BR directors told the government it could not support plans to review the
annual contribution to the pension scheme made under the Transport Act 1980.
The BR board also rejected two government options to provide benefits for
current and deferred pensioners - those who have left BR employment but have
not yet reached retirement age. One proposal involved running the pension
scheme as a closed fund with current assets. In the other the government
would take a portion of the pension scheme's assets for itself, guarantee
annual increases in line with inflation but would rule out any improvements
in benefits.
</TEXT>
