<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Unions settle for pay rises under 4%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE trade unions are accepting the lowest wage increases since the
recession of 1987.
Settlements in four leading industries - electronics, motors, shipbuilding
and steel - suggest this year's spring wage offensive will yield rises of
less than 4 per cent for most workers.
After cuts in overtime payments and bonuses are taken into account, overall
real earnings are likely to increase by less than 2 per cent this year.
Meanwhile, two government surveys predicted the economy would start to
recover from the third quarter.
Many Japanese industries are expected to reach pay settlements this week.
The low increases reflect the drive at most manufacturing companies to cut
costs after a third year of falling profits.
In the middle of the wage round several leading companies such as Nissan and
telecom group NTT announced sweeping job cuts. This has set the context for
wage bargaining.
Unions in the electrical appliance industry have agreed a 3.6 per cent rise
in basic wages, down by 1.1 percentage points on last year's increase, while
steel unions have accepted 2.6 per cent, the lowest rise for four years,
about 1 point down on last year's rise.
Toyota, the biggest car maker, yesterday agreed an increase of about 3.8 per
cent or Y11,000 (Pounds 64) a month, the lowest increase since 1987.
Only the shipbuilding and heavy machinery industry so far have reached
settlements over 4 per cent.
The news on pay deals comes as the Economic Planning Agency's index of
leading indicators, which predicts the state of the economy three to six
months ahead, rose sharply to 50 per cent in January. A reading above 50 per
cent is a sign that the economy is expected to grow. The index of leading
indicators has been below 50 per cent for more than 10 months.
Officials at the EPA were cautious about reading too much into one month's
figures. They pointed out that industrial production had yet to recover, and
inventories were still growing. The index rose from 30.8 per cent in
December, partly because of a surge in machinery orders and lower commodity
prices.
However the EPA's index of coincident indicators, which shows current
conditions, suggests the economy is still deeply depressed. The index was 11
per cent in January.
A Finance Ministry survey of large companies found most expected improvement
after July.
</TEXT>
