<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Canberra warned on federal deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Bernie Fraser, governor of the Reserve Bank of Australia, yesterday
warned the government that recovery from the 1990-91 recession could not be
sustained without a reduction in the federal budget deficit.
Mr Fraser's warning accompanied a widely-forecast reduction of half a
percentage point in official interest rates to 5.25 per cent, the 14th cut
since rates peaked at 18 per cent in early 1990.
Lower interest rates would assist business cash flows and encourage
investment. But the budget deficit 'will need to be reduced over the medium
term to provide room for a rising level of business investment', he said.
The deficit is forecast to reach ADollars 15.9bn (Pounds 7.7bn) this year,
equivalent to 4 per cent of gross domestic product (GDP). The government
claims that economic growth will reduce the deficit to 1 per cent of GDP by
1996-97.
Meanwhile, Mr Paul Keating, the prime minister, announced the promotion of
11 backbenchers in a reshuffle which stamps his authority on the Labor
government following its victory in last week's federal election.
However, Mr Keating delayed the announcement of portfolios until today,
apparently to avoid distracting media attention from challenges to the
leadership of both conservative opposition parties.
The prime minister also postponed announcing senior bureaucratic
appointments and changes in departmental structures which will accompany the
revamped government.
Several senior ministers were sacked, including Mr John Kerin, trade
minister, who was briefly treasurer (finance minister) in 1991. Mr John
Dawkins, the present treasurer is expected to retain his post.
Mr John Hewson, leader of the Liberal party, the largest partner in the
opposition coalition, comfortably defeated a challenge from Mr John Howard,
a former leader. Mr Tim Fischer, leader of the National party, was also
re-elected.
</TEXT>
