<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Rabin seeks to revive spirit of 1948
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL'S government is coming under increasing public criticism for its
failure either to stem the worsening tide of political violence or to make
progress in Middle East peace negotiations.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, the prime minister, who last week cut short a visit to the
US because of the situation at home, yesterday sought to invoke the spirit
of 1948 when the State of Israel was created. He reminded the public that
without the toughness shown by his generation, Israel would never have been
born.
'The Israeli public must return to what it once was: a fighting nation, a
coping nation, a nation which knows that in the current confrontation the
winner is the one who does not tire or become seized with fear,' he earlier
told the Knesset (parliament). President Chaim Herzog added his appeal for
public calm.
Mr Rabin won last June's general election on the twin policies of toughness
on security issues and quick progress towards a negotiated peace agreement
with the Palestinians. His emotional appeal to the public underlines how
little progress he has made on either issue.
On Monday night several Israelis were hurt in west Jerusalem as police with
water cannon battled hundreds of demonstrators protesting at the
government's inability to halt the wave of random stabbings by Arabs and the
deaths of soldiers ambushed in the Gaza Strip and West Bank.
Since Mr Rabin ordered the expulsion of 415 men from the occupied
territories in mid-December, 12 Israelis have been killed. During the same
period Israeli forces have killed more than 70 Palestinians and wounded
hundreds more.
Mrs Hanan Ashrawi, spokeswoman for the Palestinian delegation, said talks
with Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, would be held in
Washington on Friday in a new effort to resolve the issue of the expelled
Palestinians.
