<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Vietnam's PM to meet businessmen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Japanese government is planning to show the wonders of modern capitalism
to Mr Vo Van Kiet, the Vietnamese prime minister, who arrives in Japan today
on a visit that will reflect his country's emergence from diplomatic
isolation.
Japanese officials see the five-day visit as an opportunity to introduce the
Vietnamese leader to leading business executives and to reinforce the idea
that Tokyo will have a growing political role in south-east Asia.
The visit, the first by a Vietnamese prime minister since Tokyo and Hanoi
established diplomatic relations 20 years ago, comes as Japanese companies
are rapidly expanding their investments in Vietnam. By the end of November,
28 direct investments worth Dollars 305m (Pounds 215m) had been made.
Mr Vo Van Kiet is regarded by Japanese officials as an important force
behind Vietnam's economic reform programme, and Tokyo will indicate to him
that aid will continue to flow into the country, as long as reform stays on
track.
Last November, Japan provided a Y45.5bn (Pounds 266m) commodity credit,
ending a 14-year ban on aid to Hanoi that had been maintained in sympathy
with US concerns about servicemen missing in action during the Vietnam war.
However, Japanese officials are planning to raise concerns about the
continuing Vietnamese influence on the Cambodian army, which they see as a
potential obstacle to peace there.
