<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Craxi receives 11th warning of investigation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE central position of Mr Bettino Craxi, the former Socialist leader, in
Italy's corruption scandals was underlined yesterday when Milan magistrates
issued him with an 11th separate notice that he was under investigation for
alleged illicit funding of political parties.
The latest notice was part of a batch affecting seven deputies and senators
served by Milan magistrates. Apart from alleged illicit party funding, the
magistrates are seeking to investigate allegations of corruption and the
illegal receipt of money relating to contracts from Anas, the state roads
authority, and Acea, the Rome electricity company.
All but one of the seven parliamentarians are already involved in one or
several corruption scandals. Mr Craxi received his first notice of
investigation on December 15, and on March 9 the parliamentary commission
responsible for immunity issues agreed to waive his immunity to face
corruption charges relating to the first seven requests by Milan
magistrates.
Mr Craxi has consistently denied any wrong-doing and claims the magistrates
have deliberately sought to destroy him and the Socialist party. However,
both Mr Giorgio La Malfa and Mr Renato Altissimo have been forced to resign
respectively from the leadership of the Republican and Liberal parties
because of allegations they received illegal funds.
Also yesterday, Mr Severino Citaristi, the former treasurer of the Christian
Democrats, was served with his 21st notice of investigation for alleged
corruption. This is almost double the number of notices served on Mr Craxi,
and by a long shot the record number in the current scandals.
The Christian Democrats now have 31 parliamentarians caught up in
magistrates' investigations.
The party yesterday sacked most of its national executive to try to clean up
its image. The executive was cut from 48 to 15 permanent members.
To underline the reforming nature of the meeting of the council which voted
in the new executive, party president Rosa Russo Jervolino told members
touched by the scandal to stay away.
</TEXT>
