<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Spain's Socialists in funds scandal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SPANISH tax inspectors yesterday confirmed reports that the ruling Socialist
party had financed itself illegally in the late 1980s by selling phantom
consulting services to big business.
The revelations come as polls show the Socialists slipping badly with a
general election due later this year.
Confirmation of illicit financing, after two years of vehement denials by
the party leadership, has renewed opposition hopes that corruption will
become a decisive issue ahead of the election. The inspectors, provided by
the Finance Ministry, said that consulting companies operated by senior
party officials had taken receipts of Pta1bn (Pounds 6m) from some of
Spain's largest banks and industrial companies between 1987 and 1990.
For the past two years, newspapers have been alleging that these companies -
including Banco Central, Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, Asea Brown Boveri's Spanish
subsidiary, Catalana de Gas and the Pryca supermarket chain - paid money to
two companies in return for expensive reports on their sectors of business.
Hardly any of the companies have since been able to produce reports for
which they paid, on occasion, more than Pta100m, some saying they had been
lost.
The inspectors implied that those reports which had been produced had been
hastily cobbled together by the business clients.
They said these clients owed about Pta437m in unpaid taxes.
The 'consulting' companies involved, Filesa and Time Export, were controlled
by Mr Carlos Navarro, the former treasurer of the Socialist parliamentary
party, and Mr Josep Maria Sala, administrative secretary of the Catalan
Socialist party and a member of the party's national executive. Money taken
from business 'clients' was then used to pay socialist election expenses
and, to disguise that, they took receipts not from party suppliers but from
companies run by Ms Aida Alvarez, the Socialist party's national financial
co-ordinator until 1986.
The Socialist party said yesterday that it would not try to protect the
parliamentary immunity of anyone implicated in the scandal, but it is not
clear whether the investigating judge, Mr Marino Barbero, will now begin
trial proceedings.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
