<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Russia in Crisis: Press and TV fear congress more than
Yeltsin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Boris Yeltsin's decree putting Russian press and broadcasting
media 'under his protection' sounded like a Mafia godfather making an offer
one could not refuse rather than a reformer protecting liberty.
However, it is not generally seen as repressive, partly because the
draconian-sounding part of the decree - that armed guards would be posted at
the doors of newspapers and broadcasting stations - does not seem to have
materialised. As Mr Valentin Starkov, editor of the mass circulation
Argumenti i Fakti, pointed out yesterday, he had had militia men on the door
for the past year, paying several million roubles a year for the privilege.
'We need them to protect us against the mad people who want to come and see
me about something,' he said.
Though Russia's press is immeasurably freer than it was even under Mr
Mikhail Gorbachev's glasnost regime, it is still significantly constrained.
The editors of both main state television channels, Mr Vyacheslav Bragin of
Ostankino and Mr Oleg Poptsov of Russian TV, were appointed by Mr Yeltsin
and are political, not industry, figures. Most of the national and Moscow
press is pro-Yeltsin, even if often critically so.
On Mr Khasbulatov's side are only a clutch of communist and nationalist
papers, with a couple of papers taking a wavering centrist line.
The once-dominant Pravda, now owned by a Greek millionaire and still taking
the communist line, has been a strong supporter of Mr Khasbulatov. Its
splash headline yesterday was 'The people need a strong Russia: the
president needs a strong shock'.
Sovyetskaya Rossiya, the communist-nationalist paper of the Russian
communist party, takes a similar line. The influential far-right weekly Den
prefers Mr Khasbulatov to Mr Yeltsin but really likes neither, while
Rabochaya Tribuna, controlled by the Union of Industrialists, and Trud, once
the organ of the trade unions and still reflecting their view, are often
strongly critical of Mr Yeltsin - though they have preferred, in these early
days of presidential rule, to sit on the fence.
Mr Starkov, whilecritical of Mr Yeltsin, believes the biggest threat is from
parliament.
'I recently received a packet of papers from the parliamentary press office,
including a speech from Ruslan Khasbulatov, with a request that I print it.
On the basis that the speech had already been aired on TV, I didn't. Even
when this paper was controlled by the central committee of the Communist
Party, we didn't print speeches like that.'
The possibility of a takeover of the media by Congress is real enough: a
draft decree was drawn up during the last extraordinary Congress earlier
this month to take over TV and radio channels as well as the Itar Tass news
service.
In an earlier stand-off between Mr Yeltsin and Mr Khasbulatov, the latter
tried to repossess the daily Izvestia, once the organ of the USSR Supreme
Soviet, arguing that it was still the property of its Soviet successor, the
Russian parliament. Mr Khasbulatov did send the parliamentary guards to the
paper, but they were withdrawn without incident the next day.
Mr Starkov said: 'The president wants to be seen as a preserver of freedom:
he wants to show the country and the world his commitment to liberty. And so
I don't think there is a threat from his protection. It wouldn't accord with
the image he wants to have, to force us to do things.'
</TEXT>
