<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Russia in Crisis: Sting in tail of court's judgment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE constitutional court's judgment on President Boris Yeltsin's appeal to
the Russian people was described yesterday by a court official as 'very
mild'. But on closer inspection the judgment has all the mildness of a
ticking time bomb.
The official noted that the preamble to the judgment expressed understanding
of the president's desire to provide stability in Russia, and that the
ruling did not demand impeachment.
It is true the preamble stresses that the court agrees on the need to end
the crisis over the division of powers, on the need to continue political
and economic reform and to safeguard the unity and integrity of the country.
It is also true that there is no call for impeachment, though the Interfax
news agency said such a clause had been in early drafts of the judgment.
Further, the judgment is careful to say that the two notorious articles of
the constitution which give all power to the congress - articles 104 and 109
 -cannot be taken at face value, but must be read in conjunction with other
articles - 1, 3, 72 and 81 - which guarantee the principle of the division
of powers.
In the past Mr Yeltsin and his supporters have pointed to articles 104 and
109 as proof that the Soviet-era constitution which still governs the powers
of the different levels of government is simply impossible to work with.
But the conclusion to the six-page judgment is, in constitutional terms,
devastating. The president is judged to have broken nine provisions of the
constitution, and various provisions of the federal treaty which Mr Yeltsin
signed with leaders of the autonomous republics, regions and districts of
Russia.
The verdict by Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the parliamentary speaker, yesterday
that there were clear grounds for impeachment of the president has a clear
legal basis.
The one concession made is to say that Mr Yeltsin has a right to ask the
people for an expression of trust in himself.
But he is not, in the court's view, constitutionally able to pose a question
of relative trust between himself and the parliament (as he has said he
wishes to do), nor can he ask the people who they wish to lead the country -
president or parliament.
By centring all power into his own office, says the judgment, he destroys
the principle of division of powers. He cannot hold a referendum on a new
constitution nor on a new electoral law without the permission of congress,
since that breaks a key provision of article 104.
Above all, his declaration of 'special rule' is provided for only in
extraordinary situations (which do not at present exist), and according to a
set order, which has not been followed. The judgment is thus 'mild' only in
relation to what it was thought it might say. In fact, to have stated that
the president must be impeached would have transgressed the court's powers
and intruded on those of congress, which must make that decision. Its
preamble merely says that it agrees that life should improve.
The power of the court's judgment lies in the rehearsal of what it believes
to be the breaches of the constitution. Mr Yeltsin and his supporters have
never seriously proposed that they were acting within the constitution: they
have cast doubt on the constitution itself, called the court biased and said
that they will ignore its findings.
Most seriously, the judgment presents the congress - expected to meet on
Friday - with a momentous decision. It must either vote for impeachment as
Mr Khasbulatov urges, or, if it backs away, face political oblivion.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
