<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Russia in Crisis: EC proposal for Moscow to join free trade
zone
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE EC would negotiate an eventual common free trade zone with Russia, in an
attempt to underpin its economic reforms and political stability, under a
proposal the European Commission is expected to agree today.
The move comes as a senior EC delegation, including foreign ministers, is
due in Moscow to underline its solidarity with the reform process.
Brussels wants a mandate from EC member states to widen current negotiations
with Moscow on a so-called 'partnership' agreement. This is in response to
requests from the Russian government for an accord more like the
arrangements the Community now has with Hungary, Poland, the Czech and
Slovak republics, Romania and Bulgaria - the so-called 'Europe agreements'.
'One of the principal requests from the Russian side which the Community is
unable to fulfil within the existing directives is the inclusion in the
partnership and co-operation agreement of an evolutionary clause opening the
possibility at a future stage for free trade in goods, and for national
treatment for the establishment of companies and cross-border trade in
services,' according to a confidential Commission document.
The document, prepared by Sir Leon Brittan, external economic affairs
commissioner, in collaboration with Mr Hans van den Broek, external
political affairs commissioner, was largely agreed by senior Commission
officials on Monday.
The central idea is to work towards a common free trade zone with Russia -
and possibly other former Soviet republics - along with improved technical
and financial assistance to make this possible. The EC and its member
states, mainly Germany, already provide some two thirds of total financial
aid to the former Soviet Union and central and eastern Europe.
The Commission is looking for endorsement of the 'enlarged mandate' when EC
foreign ministers meet in Luxembourg on April 5, and for the agreement with
Russia to be politically rubber-stamped by June's Copenhagen summit of EC
heads of government.
The main difference between what it is seeking for Russia and what has been
negotiated with the east and central Europeans is that the drive towards a
free trade zone with the latter is linked to their eventual membership of
the EC. This is not on offer to Russia.
But the terms of trade Russia might get, according to the Commission
document, could be more favourable than for the east Europeans.
</TEXT>
