<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Russia in Crisis: US wants Russian summit - Washington
convinced emergency meeting on aid is needed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US government is now convinced that an emergency summit of leading
industrialised nations to consider aid to Russia is both desirable and
probably inevitable.
Until now, the administration has publicly confined itself to supporting a
special meeting of G7 finance and foreign ministers, still likely to take
place some time next month.
But senior officials have taken careful note of growing pressure from
President Francois Mitterrand of France, Mr John Major, the British prime
minister, and Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany for more immediate action.
Mr Kohl is in Washington to see Mr Clinton later this week and Mr Douglas
Hurd, the British foreign secretary, meets Mr Warren Christopher, the
secretary of state, in Washington today.
President Bill Clinton meanwhile has been prepared to move next month's
meeting with Mr Boris Yeltsin from Vancouver to Moscow or any other venue
requested by the Russian president. But the Russian government indicated
yesterday that this idea had been dropped.
Mr Clinton's advisers are becoming increasingly irritated that Japan still
apparently wishes the annual G7 economic summit, which is to take place in
Tokyo in July, to be the principal forum for discussing aid to Russia.
They believe the immediate imperative of putting together an aid package far
transcends Japan's territorial dispute with Russia over the Kurile islands
and its determination not have the annual summit upstaged. Some cannot
understand why Japan has not settled its differences with Russia.
Such an aid package would be intended to demonstrate support for Mr Yeltsin
as the best hope for continuation of economic reform in Russia.
But in a speech in Chicago on Monday, Mr Christopher sought to draw some
fine distinctions between backing for Mr Yeltsin in particular and for the
reform process in general.
While staunch in his approval of the Russian president, he also said, with
some nuance, 'our engagement with the reformers must be for the long haul,
whether they're out as well as whether they're in, whether they're down as
well as when they are up'.
But officials concede that it is difficult to find in Russia alternatives to
Mr Yeltsin to keep the momentum for reform going.
Mr George Stephanopoulos, the chief White House spokesman, is careful never
to identify in his daily briefings others in whom the US might be willing to
place confidence.
Mr Clinton's attachment to Mr Yeltsin, often compared to President George
Bush's support for Mr Mikhail Gorbachev, the president of the former Soviet
Union, is attracting some critical fire.
Yesterday, Dr Henry Kissinger, the former secretary of state, wrote in the
Washington Post that 'the US must not tie itself to any one leader of any
one government in Russia.'
He said that he personally preferred Mr Yeltsin, 'but I also believe he must
be able to stay in office by his own efforts and not through foreign
exhortations that could easily backfire.'
Senior administration officials are prepared for the fact that if Mr Yeltsin
does fall a degree of blame will be attached to Mr Clinton.
It was partly for this reason that the president, contrary to the advice of
some of his advisers, chose to hold his first formal press conference
yesterday, knowing that Russia would dominate the questions but insistent on
being given the opportunity to explain his approach in detail.
In the event, at his press conference Mr Clinton walked a similar line to Mr
Christopher's.
He endorsed Mr Yeltsin as fulsomely as might be expected but emphasised that
the greater US vital stake lay in promoting the reform process in Russia
'with or without Yeltsin.'
Asked how he would characterise the US ability to influence the immediate
course of events in Moscow, he was equally careful.
'We are not a bystander,' the president insisted, since Russian reform
needed US assistance. But ultimately the fate of Mr Yeltsin was 'in the
hands of the Russian people'.
</TEXT>
