<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Pru backs OFT over greater life costs disclosure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRUDENTIAL, the UK's largest life insurance company, yesterday broke ranks
with the Association of British Insurers and supported the Office of Fair
Trading's proposal to require much more disclosure about the cost of life
products.
Mr Mick Newmarch, the Pru's chief executive and a board member of the ABI,
said: 'The need for the industry to become much more transparent is
something I agree with.' The Pru was considering telling prospective
customers more about costs than current rules require, he said.
Such a move could force the Pru's competitors to follow - something many in
the industry are reluctant to do now.
Mr Newmarch's remarks, made at a press conference to announce the Pru's
annual results, referred to the OFT's report last week which concluded that
life companies do not tell consumers enough about their products to enable
them to choose among products, companies or sales agents.
The Treasury must consider the report and, if it agrees with its
conclusions, will ask regulators to draft rules for a new disclosure regime.
The ABI said last week it intended to urge the Treasury to reject the
report.
The ABI, however, yesterday appeared to be softening its stance. Mr Tony
Baker, director of public affairs, said: 'There are reservations and we will
be commenting to the Treasury and to the regulatory bodies. We've got to
wait for our members to consider the report, but we will not take lightly
going against anything the OFT has said.'
The OFT proposals were also strongly endorsed yesterday by Mr Joel Joffe,
founding director and former deputy chairman of Allied Dunbar, the UK's
biggest unit-linked life insurer.
Mr Joffe told the social security select committee at the House of Commons:
'It's ironic that the ABI has suddenly begun to express a concern over the
costs of regulation to the consumer. There will be intense lobbying by the
industry, allegedly in the interests of the consumer.'
This is the second time in recent months that Mr Newmarch has attacked his
industry's approach to regulation, arguing that it was undermining public
confidence in insurance products generally and would harm sales in the long
run.
In November, he called for statutory regulation if self-regulation could not
be made to work.
Observer, Page 21
Lex, Page 22
Pru advances to Pounds 406m, Page 24
