<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Survey of Japanese Financial Markets (10): Tower of Bubble
totters - The official 'price-keeping operation'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is an office block in the centre of Tokyo's financial district they
call the Tower of Bubble. With a vast and beautiful oval atrium which takes
up half of the building's floorspace, it is a monument to the excesses of
Japan in the late 1980s. It also tells the story of the rise and fall of the
infamous bubble economy.
The site used to house an NTT telephone exchange, but when computer
miniaturisation meant that the building was no longer needed, the phone
company redeveloped the site as a financial centre. It now houses securities
companies such as Nomura, Salomon Brothers and BZW.
Such was the hubris that even as land prices soared in space-hungry Japan
the architects could afford the expense of the eye-catching but unproductive
void. (Perhaps presciently, the builders fitted unusually high barriers on
the areas overlooking the 20-storey hole, presumably to deter stockbrokers
from making a traditional exit in the event of a crash.)
That collapse was not long in coming. The Nikkei index sagged from 39,000 in
late 1989 to 14,300 last August before the government stepped in with a
Keynsian public works programme to prevent the real economy from sliding
into depression, and an attempt to support the stock market with public
pension funds and postal savings.
Mr Noburu Fukuda of Nikko Securities wryly calls the share support scheme a
Price-Keeping Operation, after the UN's various peace-keeping operations
around the world; a joke shared by other Tokyo brokers. But while it may
have helped prevent the widely-feared systemic collapse of Japan's banking
and life assurance industry, the Price-Keeping Operation is slowly
throttling Japan's securities houses.
For the broking community, the problem is that trading volumes have all but
dried up. The government seems determined to put a floor under share prices
 -about 16,000 on the Nikkei index - to support the banks' and insurance
companies' capital bases. But if the government has put a floor under
prices, then almost everyone else has built the ceiling. Speculative Tokkin
funds, individuals, companies with unrealised capital gains, banks and life
insurance companies with a shortage of liquid assets would all like to sell
shares above 18,000.
A stalemate between the government and investors has left the stock market
in a very narrow trading range. Few would like to guess when the market will
break out - or even in which direction the move is likely to come. That
leaves very little reason to trade, and as speculative activity has dwindled
the brokers' income has fallen.
Apart from executing the government's share purchases, practically the only
trade is in index arbitrage - a business dominated by foreign brokers. Most
Japanese securities houses think that the Tokyo Stock Exchange needs to turn
over at least 400m shares a day for the large brokers to break even. While
that is much lower than the peak volumes of 800m shares a day in 1988,
current turnover is only 200m shares a day. Brokers large and small are
haemorrhaging cash.
Opinions vary about how easily the brokers can cope. Alicia Ogawa of Salomon
Brothers thinks that there is plenty the securities houses can do. 'The big
four houses, Nomura, Daiwa, Nikko and Yamaichi, have done a lot to get costs
down,' she says. 'In September 1991 they needed a TSE turnover of 450m
shares to break even; now that's down to 350m. They can chop bonuses, cut
out new recruits, and have a higher natural wastage than many other Japanese
businesses.
'About 25 per cent of their costs are in areas such as advertising and
entertainment - which can clearly be cut back. Smaller overseas operations
and even some domestic branches are being closed or merged.'
But Noburu Fukuda at Nikko is not so sure. 'I am struggling with this
problem and it is not easy. People often say that we shed labour naturally
as women leave to get married. But fewer are leaving, perhaps because of the
economic difficulties. We can try to cut our costs by sending staff to our
affiliated companies, but then our affiliates have their own problems and
want to send people to us.
'We need to ride this together and perhaps that means forgetting bonuses.
Still, we must be careful that the pain is shared fairly. Top management
will need to sacrifice more.' Nikko is budgeting on a long run market
turnover of about 350m shares a day, but that looks optimistic. 'If things
don't start to improve soon, we will have to think again,' Mr Fukuda
concedes.
Indeed, the securities industry has made a rod for its own back by
responding so slowly. The stock market peaked over three years ago, yet it
is only in the last 12 months that securities firms started to take
significant action.
That is especially true of the second tier securities houses which are
arguably most at risk because they expanded most rapidly in the late 1980s,
and now have cost structures a long way out of balance with any likely
incomes. 'Firms like Sanyo Securities and New Japan must really be hurting,'
thinks Ms Ogawa. 'They geared up the most during the 1980s, and still need
turnover to exceed 600m shares."
If the medium sized firms are in the deepest trouble, that is only cold
comfort to the large and small brokers. Small firms are heavily dependent on
individual investors who have mostly quit the field. And while they operate
out of cheaper offices, with much lower overheads, income has almost dried
up.
Selling investment trusts managed by the large brokers which paid high
commission rates was an important source of above average commission. That
business is fading fast. Many small brokers have relationships with large
firms and look to them for salvation. They may look in vain.
Large firms, fearful that they will set a general precedent, are reluctant
to commit themselves to rescuing any but their closest allies. At least a
proportion of the smaller brokerage firms will be allowed to go out of
business.
That network of relationships is a problem for the large firms. Not only do
they have equity stakes and other ties to many small and embattled firms,
but they also have financing subsidiaries which have suffered as badly as
many banks in the property bubble. Once those subsidiaries are accounted
for, the balance sheets of even very large firms may start to look
stretched.
If the most likely scenario for the Japanese broking community is for a
rationalisation of small firms and the strengthening of the big four at the
expense of the upstart pretenders, then that outcome is crucially dependent
on the ability of the large firms to exploit the situation. The size of the
black holes in their balance sheets will determine not only the ability of
the large firms to capitalise on the exposed middle market, but also the
number of their smaller brethren they can afford to rescue.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
