<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Survey of Czech Republic (9): EC warning causes concern -
The ailing steel industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE is an air of resignation in Prague following the latest bout of
sabre-rattling between Washington and the European Community over steel
subsidies and recent EC warnings against 'excessive' steel exports and
dumping by east European producers.
Officials know that as a small producer, the Czech Republic can do little to
arrest the wave of protectionist sentiment in the west. Mr Vladimir Dlouhi,
trade and industry minister, dismisses the EC charges as unfounded. 'There
is no dumping. There are no direct subsidies to steel mills, and practically
no indirect subsidies.' He says if the EC really wants to help eastern
Europe, it should open its markets rather than erect protectionist barriers.
Mr Vladimir Petr, director for steel at the industry ministry, takes a more
conciliatory line. 'We will do what is agreed, and we're talking to our
companies to make sure they behave themselves.' In the meantime, he says,
Czech steel makers will look for new markets elsewhere.
But there is no masking the disappointment with the EC over its threats
against a domestic industry that is already in the throes of a crisis and
whose restructuring will cause many job losses. The drive for modernisation
and higher productivity is expected to see employment in the steel industry
fall from around 85,000 today to 45,000 by 2000. Much of the burden of job
losses will fall on the north-eastern region of Ostrava near the Polish
border which is home to the Czech Republic's three biggest steel plants, Mr
Petr says.
To add to the uncertainty, new agreements with the EC will have to be drawn
up separately with the Czech Republic and Slovakia following the break-up of
the former Czechoslovak state on January 1. Czech and Slovak producers are
operating on the basis of agreements drawn up between the EC and
Czechoslovakia in 1990/91 with quotas for this year expected to remain at
their 1992 levels. This allowed for exports to the EC of 1.1m tonnes of
rolled products annually, and 60,000 tonnes a year of steel pipes.
Officials admit exports of rolled steel to the Community have doubled since
1990 when they totalled 783,300 tonnes compared to 1.5m tonnes last year,
but they say this had nothing to do with dumping.
Czechoslovak producers faced with the collapse of markets in eastern Europe
and the former Soviet Union, a sharp decline in domestic consumption, and a
freeze on the domestic arms industry imposed after Czechoslovakia's 'velvet
revolution' in 1989, looked to western Europe for markets. They were
competitive because production costs are about 30 per cent lower than in the
EC, Mr Petr says. 'Wages and transport costs are low and we have cheap iron
ore from the Ukraine, but this will not last and the next three or four
years are going to be difficult.'
Officials say the Community also conveniently overlooked that Czechoslovakia
exported steel to the former East Germany when setting the quotas.
This gives no comfort to companies already struggling to survive such as the
giant Poldi United Steel Works in Kladno, some 30km west of Prague. In
February, the company appealed for urgent financial help from the government
to overcome a serious financial crisis that had already forced it to
temporarily close down two of its plants.
During the past two years, Poldi has cut its workforce by half to around
10,000 workers, with another 3,000 jobs due to go this year. Poldi's
troubles came to a head following the state-owned electricity utility's
decision to sharply reduce power supplies to the company which it said owed
it CzK260m. Poldi has debts of CzK5.1bn, but it is also owed almost CzK3bn
in unpaid bills from more than 200 customers including some of the largest
Czech companies. To overcome this debilitating circle of bad debt, it wants
the government to inject CzK1bn into the company and to allow it to raise
another CzK1bn through the sale of real estate assets.
A resumption of economic growth after the past two years' sharp fall in
output would help, but it will be a long and painful haul until the Czech
steel industry recovers. Total steel production in the former Czcheslovakia
has fallen by 20 per cent from 14.9m tonnes in 1990 to below 12m tonnes last
year, according to the latest estimates, and it is set to continue to fall.
Long-term prospects for the industry will depend on the success of
restructuring as well as on access to markets. A study commissioned by the
government and completed last June favours privatising all the Czech
Republic's steel industry with the larger companies to be split up into
smaller units to make them more attractive to foreign investors.
As a first step towards privatisation, 11 companies have been turned into
joint stock companies for which the government is hoping to find foreign
partners for joint ventures. What the government would like is to repeat the
successful sale last month of a wheel-making subsidiary of Nova Hut, the
large steel and metallurgical group, to Hayes Wheels International of the
US. The company makes about 1.5m car wheels annually, but under the
agreement with Hayes, production will be raised to 11.5m wheels a year with
supplies going to leading car manufacturers in Europe including General
Motors, Volkswagen, Renault and Mercedes.
As part of the restructuring plan, Czech steel production will be lowered
from last year's 7m tonnes to 5.5m tonnes a year by 2000. The aim is to
raise productivity and improve quality while reducing energy and raw
materials consumption. This will help to save resources as well as maintain
the competitiveness of local industry as labour and other production costs
rise.
Three large projects include construction of a new rolling mill in Vitkovice
and of a mini-mill for Nova Hut, each with an 800,000 tonnes a year
production capacity; and another mini-mill in Trinec to produce cables.
Total investment for the three projects will be CzK12.9bn spread over four
years. 'All of these priority actions should give a good return on the
capital invested,' Mr Petr says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
