<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Survey of Japanese Financial Markets (5): Known for know-how
 -Morgan Stanley bucks the trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OFFICES of Morgan Stanley Japan, in central Tokyo, are protected by dour
security guards, placed there after the company received bomb threats.
As the Tokyo stock market has continued to slump, Morgan's Japanese
operations have made the US securities house one of the few to buck the
trend. But its high profitability (using the newest computer technology,
innovative but complex strategies, large capital backing) has faced
criticism from frustrated local brokers who see their losses mount.
For the six months to September, Morgan Stanley reportedly made Y12.6bn in
pre-tax profits, seven times as much as that of Daiwa Securities, the second
largest Japanese broker. Japanese brokers rely heavily on commission from
clients; they have been hit by the plunge in trading volumes. On the other
hand, the leading American brokers make profits on trading stocks,
currencies and bonds for their own accounts. Morgan Stanley has dominated
the stock index arbitrage market, securing profits from the difference in
the cash stock and futures markets.
Japanese brokers do not have the technology in risking their own capital in
the same way; they have been left behind. Moreover, local financial
authorities have quickly blamed stock index arbitrage trading and
derivatives trading, including futures and options, as the reason for the
sluggish stock market.
Trading volatility and volumes for the derivatives markets have declined as
fees have been raised and trading restrictions implemented over the past two
years. The government's support operation for the stock market - pumping in
public funds, including postal savings and public pension money - is also
watering down share price movement.
Mr Takeo Kani, chairman of Morgan Stanley Japan, says the fall in profit
chances is inevitable. 'It's the economic fundamentals which are hurting the
stock market, not derivatives trading,' he says.
However, Mr Kani says the company has developed strategies from its
experience in the past bear markets of New York and London. It also has
expertise in structured products - and a large investor base in the US and
Europe. Such skills were recently sought by the Bank of Tokyo, which issued
a perpetual subordinated bond structured with a convertible option which
allows investors to exchange the bond with the bank's shares during the
first 10 years of issuance.
Not only was it the largest yen-denominated overseas offer, but the issue
was also the first capital raising programme by a Japanese bank to be placed
with genuine European and Asian investors, instead of affiliates and
companies with close business ties. 'Morgan Stanley is known for its
know-how in equity related products, and has an excellent placement
ability,' says a Japanese banker.
Morgan Stanley has also bravely broken into the local corporate bond market,
becoming the first foreign securities house to lead a domestic issue. Morgan
introduced the fixed-price re-offering system, to enhance the transparency
in fixing the price of bonds placed with investors. Last year it began
market-making NTT shares, activating a secondary market which previously was
almost non-existent.
Morgan Stanley's future profitability in Tokyo will depend on the speed of
financial deregulation. The slowdown of deregulation in the debt
securitisation market has disappointed leading US houses in the area.
'The potential of Tokyo as an international financial market is very big,'
says Mr Kani. Regulatory restraints, however, have hampered the growth of
the market: the number of products allowed is limited. The Tokyo market's
importance among global capital markets relies heavily on the willingness of
the financial authorities to accept further financial innovation, especially
from foreign securities houses.
</TEXT>
