<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Survey of Japanese Financial Markets (4): No price movement,
no profits - Foreign brokers are forced to restructure their operations on
an ebbing market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TIDE has turned for foreign brokers in Tokyo. Those which had raked in
profits, despite faltering volume on the Tokyo stock market, are now being
forced to restructure their operations.
A recent announcement by Salomon Brothers that it would cut 10 per cent of
its staff in Japanese equities, signalled the demise of computer-led program
trading (which foreign brokers, especially the US houses, excelled in).
While Japanese houses, which rely heavily on commission from investors,
faced a plunge in revenue caused by the market slump, leading foreign
brokers had managed to make money from trading their own capital using
computer-led investments.
Japanese brokers persuaded the financial authorities to clamp down on
arbitrage between the cash market and stock index futures - locking in
profits between the cash and futures markets. Market share of foreign
brokers, which have greater expertise in futures and options techniques,
rose to some 20 per cent; sharply higher than the 3 per cent rise during the
first half of 1988.
However, the market slump has finally caught up with Wall Street technology.
The Japanese government badly wants to keep the stock market above 16,000
before the financial year closes in March. It has pumped in public pension
funds and postal savings to support share prices. Large investors, including
banks and insurance companies, have been ordered to stop selling.
'There are no profits where there is no price movement,' says an arbitrageur
at a UK brokerage. Furthermore, the increase in efficiency of the markets
has depressed arbitrage possibilities, as Japanese and smaller foreign
houses have rushed into the arbitrage business. Some foreign arbitrageurs
reckon profit opportunities in the Tokyo market will be gone within three
years.
Meanwhile, an increasing number of foreign houses, reliant on client orders,
have met the same fate as their Japanese counterparts as trading volumes
have plunged to a quarter of the peak of a daily average of over 1bn shares
in 1988.
County NatWest, the securities arm of National Westminster, announced a
total withdrawal from the Tokyo market last December - the first foreign
broker to give up membership of the Tokyo Stock Exchange. Merrill Lynch
Japan announced the closure of its three retail branches. UK brokers,
including SG Warburg and Baring Securities, have also been cutting
overheads.
The winners in the current stagnant market will be securities houses with
enough capital and technology to introduce innovative products to the
Japanese market. One area in which US houses have become active is the
corporate bond market. More Japanese companies have started to dip into the
domestic straight bond market for funds, as equity-linked financing has
become difficult.
Domestic corporate bond issues surged 26.3 per cent durinbg 1992 to
Y3,010bn, and the ministry of finance also endorsed the development of the
corporate bond market by easing issuance rules.
Morgan Stanley has been the first foreign house to enter the domestic
underwriting business, with Japan's first fixed-price deal for Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone in 1991, paving the way for other Japanese companies
to use the fixed-price re-offering system in the domestic bond market.
Until the NTT issue, domestic corporate bonds were issued by the 'proposal
method', by which underwriting was awarded to the securities house with the
highest bid. The excessive competition for underwriting contracts led to
unrealistic offering prices. Mr Masaaki Nogawa, at NTT, says the company had
asked Japanese securities houses to come up with a more transparent system,
but got only lukewarm responses at the time.
Japanese houses, including Nomura Securities, admit that the domestic bond
market has taken off as a result of the NTT launch. Last year, Morgan
Stanley underwrote an NTT issue - the first in Japan - which allowed
investors to trade the bonds during the offering period. Until then,
investors had been forced to hold the bonds until the offering period was
over, making investors vulnerable to market movements.
The new methods employed by Morgan have enhanced liquidity in the secondary
market of domestic corporate bonds. Leading US houses and large Japanese
brokers have started to market-make corporate bonds, giving prices for which
they will buy and sell.
Financial deregulation in Japan, however, may pose a threat to the foreign
brokers' newly established businesses. From April, banking affiliates will
enter the bond underwriting business, as the gradual easing of barriers
between the banking and securities industries takes place.
Long-term credit banks, including Industrial Bank of Japan and Long Term
Credit Bank, which have close ties with corporate Japan because of their
traditional role of providing long-term funds, will be the first to enter
the securities business.
An official at a leading US securities house claims that if banks'
affiliates aim for market share, as Japanese banks have done in their
traditional territories, foregoing profitability, the fledgling market could
collapse.
Salomon was also disappointed recently by the approval of yen-denominated
perpetual bond issues by Japanese banks, which have long been restricted
from issuing yen-denominated bonds as it could intrude on the lending of the
long-term banks. The approval from the ministry of finance came after
Salomon's sale of foreign currency subordinated bond issues by Japanese
banks, repackaged into a yen product.
Although foreign brokers have been the leading force in trying to bring in
innovative products, and pushing for financial deregulation in Japan, they
may face increasing pressure as new markets open to Japanese institutions.
