<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Survey of Czech Republic (6): Western ties cemented -
Foreign policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE withdrawal of Soviet forces from central Europe and the consequences
which flowed from the failed Moscow coup of August 1991 have lifted the
danger of military or political pressure from the east after decades of
domination by Moscow. But, ideally, the Czech Republic, like the other
liberated states of the former Soviet empire, would like to guarantee its
future role in Europe by membership of an extended European Community and a
restructured Nato.
'Since the Czech Republic shares the same democratic values with the Nato
countries, and since it is resolved to defend these values, it considers
full-fledged membership in Nato as its long-term and irreversible goal,'
according to a foreign policy statement from the foreign ministry. For good
measure it adds: 'The republic considers an American military presence as a
guarantee of long-term European stability and also sees Czech membership in
the West European Union as its long-term goal.'
As Mr Josef Zielenic, the foreign minister, points out, the Czech divorce
from Slovakia underlines the western character of the new state. It no
longer has a common border with Hungary or Ukraine and has severed the
Danube link which physically links southern central Europe with the Balkans.
Specifically the divorce also leaves Prague free from entanglement in the
international dispute between Slovakia and Hungary over the future of the
controversial Gabcikovo dam, south east of Bratislava.
The maintenance of good relations with Slovakia has become a foreign policy,
not an internal matter, but no less important for that. Slovakia's desire
for its own international status and symbols was one of the main driving
forces behind the divorce. The two states retain important trade, financial
and, above all, human links which will have to be fostered on a new basis.
Further to the east, the potential for economic decline spilling over into
unpredictable political instability, remains considerable and the Czech
Republic, again like other states in the region, fears becoming an
uncomfortable buffer zone between hungry job seekers from the east and an
increasingly protectionist west.
But while diplomats speak of 'monitoring' developments in eastern and
south-eastern Europe and seeking opportunities for business and economic
co-operation, the main emphasis of Czech diplomacy and business will be 'to
strive for the balanced relations of partnership and co-operation with
Germany'. This is hardly surprising given the chequered history of relations
between the two states in this century and the importance of Germany as the
republic's main trade partner and most important source of future
investment.
Beyond Germany the Czech Republic also seeks to 'extend friendly relations
with the US, France and Britain and other member states of the EC and EFTA
with whom it sees its future to be ever more closely linked'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CZZ  Czech Republic, East Europe.
    SKZ  Slovakia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
