<PROFILE>_AN-DCXCKAEIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Survey of Czech Republic (7): Changes create problems -
Reforms have revitalised the banking system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE years into a radical reform programme, the Czech government has yet to
reap the fruits of its efforts to transform a centralised financial system
in which banks were little more than a conduit for distributing money, into
a competitive and efficient financial services sector.
Reforms have already changed the Czech Republic's banking system beyond
recognition from what used to be essentially a cash economy, in which money
transfers took weeks if not months, and where credit cards and cheque books
were unknown. But much remains to be done to achieve western standards.
'There are three main problem areas. The legal environment is incomplete; on
the operational side there are still considerable delays and the
introduction of new technology has been slow; and risk assessment is poor
and information on which to evaluate risk is unreliable,' says a senior
foreign banker.
The recent spectacular and rapid expansion of the banking sector also
highlighted a shortage of qualified staff and led to widespread poaching.
Only about half of bank employees have been in banking for more than a year,
and there are few experienced operations staff.
Mr Richard Salzmann, chairman of Komercni Banka, the largest commercial
bank, explains. 'Five years ago there was one big bank, the Statni Banka,
which was the central bank and a commercial bank at the same time. About 70
per cent of the Statni Banka's reserves were taken from the Czech and Slovak
savings banks. In 1990, it was split up into four banks (including an
independent central bank and Komercni Banka). After that, many more new
banks were created.'
Today there are about 70 banks including several foreign institutions active
on the rapidly expanding Czech market. Komercni Banka provides a good
example of the pace of developments. In 1990, it had 7,500 employees, 83
branches, and around 5,000 clients consisting of state companies and
agencies, and co-operatives. Today, it has 16,000 employees, 450 branches
and around 300,000 clients - about half the Czech Republic's 700,000 bank
accounts.
That experience was repeated across the spectrum of Czech banks which were
joined by the arrival of a large number of foreign banks including
Creditanstalt of Austria, Citibank of the US, Barclays of the UK, ABN-Amro
of the Netherlands, BNP-Dresdner Bank, among others.
The foreign banks benefited from their ability to offer better and faster
services than local banks. But while their arrival on the Czech scene helped
to shake up the local market, they have only a small portion of the market
which continues to be dominated by the big Czech banks. Government hopes
that opening the market to foreign banks would stimulate competition have
been disappointed.
It is early days yet, and the Czech banks face a number of challenges. Under
the previous communist regime, the banking system accumulated a large volume
of bad debts - often the result of loans extended to companies on government
orders. Many of these loans will never be paid back. To overcome this
crippling burden and to give the banks a fresh start, the government decided
to clean up the banks' balance sheets in one fell swoop by allowing them to
hive off the greater part of their non-performing loans and transfer them to
the Konsolidacni Banka (Consolidation Bank), an institution specifically
created to absorb these debts.
In 1991, about one third of Komercni Banka's CzK250bn assets was disposed of
in this way. 'The idea was to concentrate all bad loans into the
Consolidation Bank. We also sold to the bank some other bad debt which might
be redeemable in the long term,' Mr Salzmann says. The Consolidation Bank,
he says, is the 'dustbin of the financial system'.
The hope is that the Consolidation Bank will be able to get some of the
loans repaid, and sell some of the bad debt on the market. The rest will
have to be repaid by the National Property Fund, an institution established
to handle the privatisation process and which has become a large shareholder
in a large number of companies.
But in spite of this cosmetic clean-up of the banks' balance sheets, another
problem looms. Next month a new bankruptcy law comes into effect which could
result in a wave of business failures.
The collapse of markets in the former Comecon trade bloc, recession in the
west, and a severe decline in domestic output, have left a large number of
companies deeply in debt to one another due to lack of funds. 'This has been
a lousy way of compensating for the shortage of liquidity in the market,'
says one banker.
No-one knows the exact volume of inter-company debt and estimates vary
widely between CzK200bn and CzK300bn. But a large number of bankruptcies
would be a blow to the commercial banks whose main lending is to companies.
It would also affect the savings institutions which remain a principal
source of funding for the commercial banks.
Banks are also under pressure to meet tough new capital ratio requirements
of 8 per cent of lending assets by the end of this year, and for the first
time, they are being audited to western standards - which it is hoped will
reveal a true picture of their financial health.
All of which will accelerate the drive to raise productivity, and the
quality and range of services. Most banks are investing heavily in new
technology, and foreign institutions have been called upon to help with
training programmes for staff that range from risk assessment to management
skills and how to deal with people.
'We can't change everything overnight. It is an unprecedented task, but the
banks must come under pressure too,' says Mr Ivan Kocarnik, finance
minister. The government does not hide that it would like the banks to make
a more sturdy contribution to the economic reform process. It now looks as
if they will have no other choice.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CZZ  Czech Republic, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6021 National Commercial Banks.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MKTS  Market data.
    TECH  Services.
</TP>
