<PROFILE>_AN-DCXCKAEHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Survey of Czech Republic (8): Ideal base for exporters - Low
cost of labour is main attraction for investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DIRECT foreign investment in the Czech Republic's part of the former
Czechoslovakia doubled last year to reach Dollars 1.2bn, in spite of
political uncertainty over the country's impending dissolution. Mr Josef
Lebl, general manager of CzechInvest, the recently established foreign
investment agency, believes this is a good omen for the future, and hopes
1993 will see even higher levels of investment.
The US was the largest investor last year accounting for 39.5 per cent of
all investments, followed by France with 20.2 per cent, and Germany which
slipped into third place with 15.6 per cent. German investors, however, have
taken the lion's share with just under 40 per cent of all foreign
investments since 1989.
The Czech Republic's main attractions for investors are its low labour
costs, at less than one tenth of German wages, and the availability of
skilled workers who can be easily trained. Its location in the centre of
Europe also makes it an ideal base from which to export westwards and
eastwards, though access to western markets is the prime consideration for
investors. The country's small domestic market of 10m people is constrained
by low per capita income.
Prospects will depend largely on economic developments outside the Czech
Republic. Local drawbacks include poor telecommunications and
infrastructure, and the lack of incentives for foreign investors.
Prime minister Vaclav Klaus says all investors - domestic and foreign -
should be treated equally, and the Czech Republic is attractive on its own
terms.
Small tax advantages are available, but officials insist incentives are not
the decisive issue and other factors are more important.
But incentives can tip the balance when companies make their choice, and the
government may be forced to change its approach in the face of strong
international competition.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CZZ  Czech Republic, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
