<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT931-1640</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DCXCKAEGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Survey of Japanese Financial Markets (3): Clear differences
in health - Advertising is distracting the banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE BANKS, struggling to overcome an increasing burden of bad loans,
have recently been distracted by debate over a less serious threat -
comparative advertising. This could highlight the differences between strong
and weak institutions.
The banks' acceptance of comparative advertising will not mean that
television viewers will see, for example, a hard-sell on lower interest
rates by Sakura Bank or a critique of competitors by Mitsubishi Bank, but it
does reflect the Bank of Japan's belief that banks should be more
distinctive.
During the clean-up after the excesses of the late 1980s, the banking
industry has insisted that the differences between the 'good' and 'bad'
banks are minimal.
Mr Yasushi Mieno, the Bank of Japan governor, has told banks to 'escape'
from a collective mentality and 'follow the management policy best suited
under the principle of self-responsibility.'
The blurring of the lines between banks in the past may have served the
purpose of leading public attention away from the most vulnerable
institutions, but there are clear differences in the health of commercial,
trust and regional banks, and in the level of their exposure to the property
and stock markets.
Japanese depositors appear to be making those distinctions, without the help
of comparative advertising.
Several regional banks with large non-performing property loans have seen a
sharp downturn in deposits, including Hyogo Bank, based in the western
Japan, which lost 16.5 per cent of its deposits in the first half, and whose
short-term deposits have fallen by an estimated 50 per cent over the past
year.
Anxious to avoid fears of a 'run' on banks, the Bank of Japan has quietly
pumped fresh funds into Hyogo Bank and asked three leading banks, Sumitomo
Bank, the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan, and the Industrial Bank of Japan,
to restructure the bank's operations. The central bank and the finance
ministry have also sent managers to Hyogo, which is portrayed officially as
an extreme case and not indicative of the industry.
But the difficulty in accepting these reassurances is that it remains
unclear how many other banks are receiving less publicised attention from
the ministry and the Bank of Japan.
In the first half, provisions or write-offs of non-performing loans by 13
regional banks around Tokyo rose 3.4 times, according to the district
financial bureau.
Calculating the exposure of banks is also made difficult by the unknown
exposure of financial company affiliates, which were encouraged, during the
late 1980s, to find customers outside the range normally dealt with by the
parent bank.
The parent may own only five per cent or less of these lenders, but Japanese
customers tend to see the large name behind the small company.
Nippon Credit Bank is having to bail out three leasing and credit companies
which were large property-related lenders, whether directly to developers or
indirectly in accepting property as collateral. The three affiliates are
estimated to have non-performing loans totalling about 20 per cent of their
outstanding loans.
'Japanese have always looked at who is the ultimate backer of a loan rather
than at the hard collateral, so people thought we were backing these three
companies, even though our links to them were not that great. People should
look at more than a company's name in doing business,' an NCB manager said.
But the name behind the name will remain important. Financiers providing
funds to National Lease, a troubled affiliate of Matsushita Electric
Industrial, the electronics company, presumed that they were doing business
with the Matsushita group. These understood relationships create a range of
obligations whose long-term costs are difficult to estimate.
A similar pattern is evident in the restructuring of Nippon Housing Loan,
established by commercial banks to provide funds to home buyers, but a large
lender to the property market during the late 1980s with the result that it
has an estimated Y1,300bn in non-performing loans out of a loan portfolio of
Y2,200bn.
The finance ministry's attempts to organise a rescue of Nippon Housing have
been complicated by farmer-run financial institutions wanting the nine
founder banks and the ministry to take responsibility. However, the
politically-influential farm institutions provided about 35 per cent of
outstanding funds to Nippon Housing, and were pumping in money when the
commercial banks were reducing their exposure.
These large rescues typically involve a sharp cut in interest rates or even
a suspension of interest repayments, though the exposure to Nippon Housing
is unlikely to be counted in non-performing loan figures.
Eight housing loan companies, which diversified into risky development
projects, are in need of assistance, but these institutions have not been
able to use the banking industry's Co-operative Credit Purchasing Company
(CCPC).
The CCPC is supposed to salvage the banking system and revive the property
market, though it has had little impact since its inauguration in late
January.
By valuing property collateral and buying loan credits, the CCPC will enable
stronger banks to quicken the write-off of non-performing loans, but it will
not provide much assistance to weaker institutions.
Japanese banks are being encouraged by the Bank of Japan to take advantage
of profits generated by favourable interest rate margins to make provisions
for or write-off as much of their non-performing exposure as possible. The
case of Sumitomo Bank is cited as a model, as it plans to write-off Y100bn
of its exposure to Itoman, a collapsed trading house.
But the Sumitomo case also highlights how much farther Japanese banks, large
and small, must travel before they overcome their bad loan problems.
Sumitomo's write-offs this year will not mark the end of its bubble era, nor
even cover the exposure to the trading house, as it has an estimated Y500bn
in loans to the Itoman group.
</TEXT>
