London Page II
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT931-1644</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DCXCKAECFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Survey of Japanese Financial Markets (1): Resistant to
change - Japan's asset-price bubble has burst, eroding profits and
relegating expansion plans to the shelf. The country's financial
institutions are under great pressure, but they will still play an important
role internationally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CREATING THE right impression is important in Japan.
The cutbacks in staff, the branch closures of brokers and banks, and the
life assurers' angry demands for better returns on shares give the intended
impression that much is changing in financial Japan, and that institutions
are finally accepting the need for a broad restructuring.
But after three years of plummeting stock prices and the collapse of the
property market the most remarkable characteristic of Japan's financial
markets is the resistance to seemingly inevitable change. The players have
yet to accept that the new financial conditions mean that they must redefine
the old relationships and reform their old ways.
There are even signs that the Japanese government, moving gradually towards
more transparent and competitive markets over the past decade, has allowed
the stock and property crash to divert attention from these goals.
'Administrative guidance' (the often opaque missives from the finance
ministry) is coming back into fashion, and policy decisions appear
increasingly designed to serve the interests of institutions - not
investors.
Relationships on the financial fringe have changed. Banks are less likely to
lend to customers outside their core clientele, and some fringe corporate
customers have sold off bank stocks. But the relationships at the centre
remain relatively stable, and the life assurers have yet to act on their
repeated threats to dump low-yielding shares.
However, the longer the share market and corporate profits remain weak, and
the larger the pile of non-performing loans, the greater the pressure for
changes to these core relationships. A surge in stock prices earlier this
month gave leading banks and brokers the impression that the worst may be
over, but the possibility remains that the real restructuring of financial
Japan may only just be beginning.
Gauging the depth of Japanese institutions' difficulties is not easy. Banks
are being encouraged by the Bank of Japan to write-off non-performing loans,
but the Y12,300bn declared by the 21 leading commercial, trust and long-term
credit banks in September is far from their total exposure.
It does not include the increasing burden of loans on which interest rates
have been shaved down to 0.5 per cent, nor loans on which token payments are
made to get round the definition of non-performing - no repayments within a
six month period. And it does not necessarily include the problem loans of
affiliates.
Mr Yasushi Mieno, the Bank of Japan governor, admits 'there is no quick
remedy' for the non-performing asset problem, and the 'process will be
accompanied by a certain amount of pain.' He recommends that banks show more
individualism, offering distinctive services and writing-off bad loans in
line with their ability to absorb losses, not in line with their
competitors.
'Each financial institution needs to escape from its conventional management
stance of doing the same as its competitors,' Mr Mieno says.
Conscious of international attention on capital adequacy standards, Japanese
banks have boosted their ratios by taking on subordinated loans and issuing
perpetual subordinated bonds; both improve the raw figures without the pain
of structural adjustment. All leading institutions will be above the 8 per
cent minimum applying at the end of this month, but these figures will
flatter the less profitable banks.
'Restructurings' overseen by Japanese banks are also, sometimes, not what
they seem. This was highlighted by a dispute this month between Azabu
Building, a 'bubble era' developer, and its main bank, Mitsui Trust and
Banking. The bank last year provided the developer with a new president and
managerial staff supposed to reassure other creditors by reducing Azabu's
Y700bn in debts through the disposal of properties.
Azabu Building presumed that the operation would be a time-biding
'restructuring", with properties shuffled around to friendly companies or
affiliates on the understanding that they would be repurchased by Azabu when
the crisis passed. But, as an Azabu official put it, 'Mitsui Trust was
trying to sell too much,' prompting the developer's founder to dismiss the
president and the other Mitsui staff.
Japan's brokers are also yet to make the deep cuts necessary to ensure their
profitability at the present market turnover and stock price levels. Not one
of the 14 largest brokers reported a net profit for the first half to the
end of September, and apart from a sudden surge in mid-March, prices and
turnover have continued on a downward trend begun in December 1989.
The Big Four brokers - Nomura Securities, Daiwa Securities, Nikko Securities
and Yamaichi Securities - are closing retail boutiques opened in shopping
centres and railway stations during the late 1980s, and cutting staff
through attrition. But they still need an average daily turnover in Tokyo of
about 400m shares, approximately double the level of recent months.
Of the 10 second-tier brokers, only those with close links to the still
powerful Nomura appear strong enough to survive without a complete overhaul.
These houses have made deeper cuts than the Big Four, but the knife must go
deeper still, as they are more reliant on trading commissions, which account
for as much as 80 per cent of their income.
The stock market's continuing weakness raises the question of what other
funding sources can be tapped by industrial companies. (They are lucky that
the life assurers are looking to return to their traditional role as lenders
to industry.
Mr Yutaka Tanaka, managing director of finance at NKK, the steel maker,
claims to have had little difficulty in finding Y220bn this year to
refinance Dollars 700m in warrant bonds issued in December 1988, and another
Y130bn in convertible bonds from July 1989. He chose bond issues in the
Euromarkets, and says his confidence came out of his belief that 'with
issues maturing, people have to find some new investment.'
Other large and respectable companies have turned to the domestic bond
market, where there were 40 issues totalling Y1,680bn in the fiscal first
half, compared to 63 issues at Y2,423bn for all of the previous year. But
the market remains heavily regulated, and the power utilities, which had the
market to themselves until the 1980s, still account for about half of the
issues.
A sign of the pressure on small companies was a decline in lending by
second-tier regional banks during February for the first time in five years.
The Regional Banks' Association blamed decline on lack of demand, but it
also reflects the unwillingness of banks to fund new corporate customers.
International companies are also finding Japanese banks more cautious. An
Asian confectionery manufacturer, having signed a lucrative contract to
supply a Japanese retail chain, told of a meeting with officials at a
Tokyo-based commercial bank which seemed to approve a loan - but a call next
day made it clear that no funds would be available.
That introversion is in contrast to the internationalism shown by Japanese
financial institutions during the 1980s. Another worrying sign is the
finance ministry's willingness to return to the wink-and-nod relationships
which tended to exclude institutions outside the inner circle in Tokyo.
Convenient rule changes - allowing life assurers to count unrealised profits
on their stock portfolios as income, and permitting banks to defer
write-downs of overvalued assets - seek to give the impression that the
worst of the crisis is over. Long-heralded reforms to demolish the wall
between banks and securities houses have been delayed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
