<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Life profits move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
News that United Friendly, the life assurance group, is examining ways of
determining ownership of its life fund and methods of distributing profits
from future life insurance profits triggered an upsurge in United shares and
similar gains in other life stocks.
Life assurance specialists said the move by United was not entirely
unexpected and follows similar ones by other life companies.
'It is a positive step forward and should put pressure on other life
companies,' commented the insurance team at Charterhouse Tilney, the
stockbroker.
Mr Youssef Ziai at Morgan Stanley adopted a much more cautious view: 'This
could be the last piece of positive news in the sector for some time and is
now fully reflected in share prices.'
United shares jumped 65 to 715p, having touched a peak 725p. Britannic and
Refuge, seen as likely candidates to adopt a similar approach to their life
funds, rose 13 per cent and 11 per cent respectively. The latter closed 112
higher at a record 1130p and the former a massive 172 up at an all-time high
of 1475p.
