<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Bass weak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further worries over the domestic brewing market were evident as Bass once
again bore the brunt of market anxiety. Kleinwort Benson was one of two
houses to chop its figures on the hotel and brewery group, blaming a
combination of tough domestic competition and increased capital expenditure
in its pub estate. The broker now expects profits of Pounds 555m, down
Pounds 18m, for this year, and for Pounds 618m, down Pounds 10m, for 1994.
NatWest Securities also raised fears over the domestic market and issued a
sell note on the stock. The house warns that the battle being joined for
market share, chiefly with Courage, will eventually be won by Bass but cost
it 'reduced profitability over several years.' NatWest cut its forecasts to
Pounds 572m in 1993 and Pounds 595m in 1994. The shares dropped 13 to 562p
in turnover of 1.6m.
