<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Airlines rise on traffic
reports as Dow eases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
EQUITIES turned narrowly lower yesterday afternoon in dull trading with only
the transportation sector showing signs of real strength, writes Karen Zagor
in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended the day down 1.62 at 3,461.68. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was off 0.04 at 448.84, while the
Amex composite rose 0.38 to 419.56. The Nasdaq composite closed 1.59 lower
at 675.03 after posting gains in morning trading. Trading volume on the NYSE
was about 232m shares and declines outnumbered rises by 967 to 887.
A surge in airline shares contributed to strong gains in the Dow Jones
transportation average which climbed 20.15 to 1,551.14.
Airline issues were lifted by reports of improved domestic traffic. An
analyst at First Boston said that domestic revenues for the industry were
about 6 per cent higher in February, above his expectations of 4.5 per cent
growth, although he expected international business to decline by as much as
9 per cent in March.
AMR, parent of American Airlines, firmed Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 63 7/8 ,
Delta Air Lines rose Dollars 2 to Dollars 51 7/8 , UAL, parent of United
Airlines, climbed Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 120 3/8 and US Air improved
Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 17 1/4 .
Ford hit a 52-week high of Dollars 53, up Dollars  1/2 after Dean Witter
Reynolds increased its rating on the stock to 'buy' from "hold'. The firm
also increased projected earnings for Ford to Dollars 2.45 a share for 1993,
from Dollars 2.25. Among other car makers, Chrysler slipped Dollars  3/8 to
Dollars 38 7/8 and General Motors closed unchanged at Dollars 39 7/8 .
Outboard Marine, a leading manufacturer of outboard motors, sank Dollars 1
7/8 to Dollars 18 5/8 after the company said that a slow-down in European
and US sales had hurt second quarter net income. Outboard Marine expects
earnings in the three months to fall below the 10 cents a share it earned a
year earlier.
Drug company shares overcame their recent depression, with Merck rising
Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 37, Glaxo Holdings adding Dollars  1/4 to Dollars
18 and Johnson&amp;Johnson gaining Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 40 1/2 .
In Nasdaq trading, shares in Retix plunged Dollars 3 5/8 to Dollars 6 1/2
after the software company said that it might break even or post a small
loss in the first quarter and predicted that revenues might fall as much as
15 per cent in the quarter.
Other technology issues were unable to hold onto their morning gains.
Canada
TORONTO prices ended higher in active trading boosted by a strong gain in
real estate stocks. Based on preliminary data, the TSE 300 composite index
gained 14.99 points to 3,598.73, with advances leading declines 342 to 319.
Volume of 61.1m shares included two blocks of Royal Bank of Canada totalling
about 2.8m shares. Real estate stocks jumped 3.87 per cent, as Cambridge
Shopping rose 1 1/8 to 16 1/8.
</TEXT>
