<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Rise in yen, Russia
fears leave Nikkei down 1.6%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SHARP rise in the yen against the dollar and European currencies, and news
of political unrest in Russia made their mark. Share prices lost ground on
selling by investment trusts and profit-taking by dealers, writes Emiko
Terazono in Tokyo.
The Nikkei average fell 292.77 or 1.6 per cent to 18,491.62, having opened
at the day's high of 18,734.72 before sliding in later trading to hit a low
of 18,489.52 just before the close.
Volume was 370m shares against Monday's 330m. Losers led gainers by 732 to
300, with 138 issues unchanged. The Topix index of all first section stocks
fell 15.79 to 1,397.91 and, in London, the ISE/Nikkei 50 index rose by 0.96
to 1,112.39.
A fall in overseas stock markets unnerved some investors but the decline was
led by the futures market, followed by arbitrage selling. Profit-taking by
foreign investors was also noted.
Concerns over the higher yen heightened as the dollar moved to record lows
against the domestic currency. Investors feared that earnings of leading
exporters would be eroded by foreign exchange losses if the yen continued to
strengthen. The dollar closed at Y115.33, down Y0.69.
Export-oriented companies weakened on volatility on the currency market.
Hitachi lost Y22 to Y760 and Fujitsu fell Y10 to Y585. Toyota Motor declined
Y10 to Y1,440.
Steels were lower on profit-taking: Nippon Steel fell Y10 to Y330 and
Kawasaki Steel lost Y6 to Y317.
Brokers were also lower as profits were taken. Nomura Securities, which has
gained 21 per cent since the beginning of the month, fell Y30 to Y1,820,
while Daiwa Securities lost Y80 to Y1,000.
Nippon Express, the parcel delivery company, gained Y14 to Y849. The issue
has been traded by short-term dealers as a Japan Railway-linked issue, and
has gained 18.7 per cent since March 1.
Mitsubishi fell Y24 to Y971, having announced on Monday that it will bail
out its financing and investment subsidiary, which accumulated stock
investment losses of Y28bn. Other trading houses, which hold heavy
unrealised losses on stock fund investments, also lost ground with Sumitomo
down Y15 to Y805.
In Osaka, the OSE average fell 100.43 to 19,462.39 in volume of 74m shares.
Roundup
Political events in Russia continued to inhibit trading in some Pacific Rim
markets.
HONG KONG paid little heed to the day's political developments in the
simmering Sino-British dispute and shares ended higher with trading
dominated by domestic speculative interest in property stocks.
The Hang Seng Index closed 57.91 higher at 6,117.95 in modest turnover of
HKDollars 2.2bn.
Property issues were in demand after unconfirmed local press reports that
the Banking Commissioner was studying ways of increasing the ceiling on
mortgage lending from 70 per cent.
Cheong Kong topped the active list, closing 60 cents higher at HKDollars
22.20. Henderson Land added 40 cents to HKDollars 17.10 while New World rose
50 cents to HKDollars 18.70.
AUSTRALIAN investors remained worried about the situation in Russia and the
market moved lower in spite of a cut in local interest rates. The All
Ordinaries index dipped 4.7 to 1659.5 in weak turnover of ADollars 271.6m.
Banks were, however, mostly beneficiaries of the rates cut. National
Australia rose 5 cents to ADollars 8.77, ANZ put on 2 cents to ADollars 3.46
while Commonwealth was steady at ADollars 7.92. However, Westpac fell 7
cents to ADollars 3.03.
Great Central Mines rose 20 cents to ADollars 11.20 after Monday's ADollars
3 surge in response to a strong overnight performance by the company's
American depositary receipts.
TAIWAN was discouraged by reports that parliament planned to complete the
privatisation of state-run financial institutions over the next three years,
since previous sell-offs had proved unsuccessful.
However, selected buying in industrials provided some support and the
weighted index finished 27.05 lower at 4,647.23 in fairly active turnover of
TDollars 72.87bn.
Electronics and food shares were the only gainers, with Acer rising 60 cents
to TDollars 23.6 and Great Wall Enterprise up 40 cents to TDollars 28.4.
MANILA was weakened by an overnight fall in Philippine Long Distance
Telephone Co (PLDT) on Wall Street, and the composite index slipped 12.35 to
1,443.25.
On the local bourse, PLDT fell 25 pesos to 870 pesos.
Manila Electric, however, was in demand, ending steady at 310 pesos, after
speculation that it will declare a 40-60 per cent stock dividend.
SEOUL rebounded after Monday's sharp fall and the composite index added 8.20
to 666.95, boosted by a government pledge to offer cheap finance to small
and medium-sized companies.
