<DOCNO>FT931-1660</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DCXCKADVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Money Markets: Repo is disappointing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GERMAN futures contracts fell back sharply yesterday after the Bundesbank
disappointed dealers by announcing a variable rate repurchase agreement in
its weekly money market operations, writes James Blitz.
For several months, the Bundesbank has been trying to wean the market away
from thinking that policy is being eased mainly through alterations in its
officially posted rates. There has been a strong focus on the repo rate,
which the Bundesbank uses to provide short dated funds to commercial banks.
There had been a strong expectation that the repo rate would be cut below
8.25 per cent this week. Instead, the Bundesbank yesterday announced a
variable rate tender, which means banks must offer competitive rates for
wholesale funds today.
Dealers believed last night that the lowest accepted bid today could be well
above 8.25 per cent because of strong competition for funds.
According to Miss Alison Cottrell of Midland Global Markets in London, banks
are particularly anxious to comply with the new minimum reserve requirements
at the end of this month, which is why cash rates are currently tight in
Germany. Call money rose as high as 8.75 per cent yesterday, close to the
Lombard rate ceiling of 9.00 per cent, before falling back to 8.58 per cent.
The Bundesbank might counter a rise in the repo rate by adding funds.
Yesterday, it pumped a large amount of liquidity into the market via
currency swaps and section 17 funds.
But the tight conditions dampened sentiment, with the June Euromark contract
falling back 19 basis points from its opening level, to close at 92.87. At
this level it is pricing 3-month money in June at 7.13 per cent, some 71
basis points below yesterday's cash level. The contract was some 37 basis
points down from last Tuesday's price, showing how much expectations have
been revised.
Short sterling futures yesterday retraced Monday's losses, in spite of a
sell-off of sterling on the currency markets. The June contract was up 5
basis points at one stage, at 94.17, but later closed unchanged at 94.12.
Three-month money closed  1/16 per cent higher at 6 1/8 per cent. The view
prevails that base rates will stay at 6 per cent in the medium term.
</TEXT>
