<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: CRA saves Pounds 90m on iron
ore project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Ralph, chief executive of CRA, Australia's second-largest mining
group, said yesterday the company had 'very closely re-examined' its
proposed Marandoo iron ore project in Western Australia and now estimated
the capital cost would be ADollars 362m (Pounds 174m), one third less than
the first estimate of ADollars 550m.
Ironically, CRA had time to complete the reassessment because it took about
16 months for environmental approvals for the mine to be completed - about
twice as long as usual.
Mr Ralph said the huge savings came partly because of a change in the
industrial relations atmosphere in Australia and the 'more mature' working
relationships between CRA and its employees.
This enabled changes to be made that saved money without compromising the
engineering. For example, originally cranes were to be incorporated into
every building because it was assumed it might not be possible to have a
driver bring a mobile crane quickly to the right place. Once it was
established that built-in cranes were not needed, building structures did
not have to be so solid.
Planned buffer stocks between processes had been eliminated and the
stockpile area reduced to take 30,000 instead of 100,000 tonnes.
Mr Ralph, at an Association of Mining Analysts meeting in London, said CRA's
Century zinc-lead-silver project in Far North Queensland, originally put on
a 'fast track' for development by 1995, would now not be operating before
1998 because of unexpectedly high levels of silica.
