<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / International Capital Markets: Swedish foreign debt rating
reduced by S&amp;P
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STANDARD &amp; Poor's, the US rating agency, yesterday downgraded Sweden's
senior long-term foreign currency debt rating to AA+, from AAA.
It said the decision, which affects Dollars 14bn of debt, reflected the size
of Sweden's budget deficit, its rising foreign debt, and the risk of slow
and uncertain economic recovery because of political pressures and the
banking crisis.
The move follows last month's downgrading by fellow US rating agency,
Moody's, which cut Sweden's long-term debt rating from Aa1 to Aa2.
S&amp;P said Swedish government debt was set to reach 80 per cent of GDP at the
end of 1994, after nearly doubling in four years, while external debt would
rise fourfold to 75 per cent of exports over the same period. Plans to cut
spending had been hampered by unemployment outlays and assistance to the
banking sector.
However, S&amp;P revised its outlook for Sweden from negative to stable as an
expression of confidence in its measures to tackle economic problems.
Mr Staffan Crona, director-general of the Swedish National Debt Office, said
S&amp;P's downgrading came as no surprise and would have only a marginal effect
on the country's borrowing costs.
</TEXT>
