<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / International Equities: Two big Spanish issues in wings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPAIN will be the source of two substantial international equity issues over
the next month with offerings from Repsol, the state-controlled energy
group, and Argentaria, the state-owned banking group.
Repsol hopes to raise Dollars 700m to Dollars 800m with the sale of about
30m shares. The offering, to be priced late next week, will result in a
reduction in the state's stake from about 50 per cent to just over 40 per
cent. The offering can be increased by 15 per cent if there is strong demand
for the shares.
Repsol has quite a broad international investor base. Under the global deal,
12m shares will be offered in the US, 7m in the UK, 6m in continental
Europe, 3.5m in Spain and 1.5m in the rest of the world. The Spanish tranche
will be offered to institutional investors as Repsol is widely held by
Spanish retail investors.
Meanwhile, investment bankers expect Argentaria to wait about a month until
Repsol is out of the way before proceeding with its IPO. The bank is 100 per
cent owned by the state, and is expected to sell up to a quarter of its
shares with Spanish retail investors likely to dominate the issue, bankers
said.
</TEXT>
