<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / International Company News: Zaiteku becomes a tainted custom
in Tokyo - Making money from money not production lines has got a bad name
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ZAITEKU is a tainted word in Tokyo. During the late 1980s, two-thirds of
listed Japanese industrial companies indulged in zaiteku - financial
engineering that ranged from the innocent exploitation of interest rate
differences to massive speculation in the stock market.
Japanese companies are still counting the cost of that 'engineering'.
Mitsubishi Corporation, the core company of Japan's largest corporate group,
this week rescued M. C. Finance, a financial subsidiary, which has Y28bn
(Dollars 237m) in unrealised losses on securities investment funds.
And two members of the Kosugi family were forced to resign at Kosugi
Industry, a textile company which makes Jack Nicklaus brand casualwear.
Kosugi is expected to announce heavy consolidated losses for the year to
January arising from a stock investment programme begun before the market
peaked in late 1989.
From the machine tool manufacturers to the great trading houses, zaiteku was
an important supplement to operating profits in the late 1980s. It was
originally defined as the management of surplus corporate funds, but took on
a speculative meaning in the late 1980s, when otherwise conservative
companies established aggressive financial subsidiaries.
Happy to support zaiteku operations when the stock market was rising,
Japanese banks, creaking under the weight of non-performing property loans,
are now wary of lending to companies with a zaiteku reputation. And even
though many of the better known manufacturers indulged, a post-'bubble'
shift of opinion now condemns companies which make money from money and not
from their production lines.
The banks' tougher line on lending comes as the burden of stock investment
losses has risen. Mitsubishi itself had unrealised losses of Y80bn on its
Y310bn in securities investment funds as at the end of September. Other
large trading houses had similar losses, including Y98bn at Marubeni and
Y92bn at Itochu, and all are now attempting to reduce their exposure.
But Itochu said not all zaiteku activities were bad, adding companies, such
as trading houses, must employ surplus funds as profitably as possible. 'For
a trading house, financial dealings are part of the main business, and so we
are not going to stop zaiteku. We are reducing securities investment funds,
but we will not stop completely,' Itochu said.
While the trading houses have the resources, including latent profits on
their long-term cross-shareholdings, to cope with losses on investment
stocks, the situation is more serious at manufacturers such Nachi-Fujikoshi,
a maker of bearings and machine tools. Nachi hoped a stock price recovery
would save it the embarrassment of writing off investment losses. But it was
forced to report a net loss of Y16.4bn for the year to November and to
suspend dividend payments for the first time since 1968.
The stock price collapse hit Nachi on two fronts. The parent company had
stock appraisal losses of Y7.96bn last year and was also forced to write off
Y5.5bn in loans and guarantees for a financial subsidiary.
'Originally, we had no intention to make profits from zaiteku, but two
ex-managers were reckless. Of course, we don't want to do any more zaiteku,
and we regret what happened in the past,' Nachi said.
Mitsubishi adds that M. C. Finance, established in 1986, was not a
securities investment company but an umbrella financial company for other
subsidiaries and affiliates. It was supposed to borrow large sums at
discount rates from banks and pass on the savings to smaller companies,
which would otherwise have paid higher interest rates.
But M. C. was later encouraged by Mitsubishi management to invest in stocks.
As with many other players, an initial windfall prompted even more ambitious
forays.
Before the stock crash, as a car machinery maker in Nagoya explained,
shareholders were asking why a company was not dabbling in stocks to boost
profits.
Mitsubishi has told M. C. to go back to basics, 'concentrating on core
activities of providing financing, accounting and related services' to group
companies. The theme is prevalent among manufacturing companies, which
confess to having strayed too far into finance and away from their core
skills.
Some companies which invested in stocks are still unable to accept that they
bore full responsibility for the risk involved. Several trading houses are
known to be negotiating with trust banks about compensation for losses
incurred, negotiations apparently prompted by the trading houses' perception
that returns were guaranteed.
There is also resentment at the tough line taken by commercial bankers, who
fear that risks may be hidden in their customers' books. An executive at a
large steelmaker said the banks have become 'obsessed' by property and stock
market exposure, and that if 'you use the word zaiteku now, bankers get
nervous'.
His sentiments were echoed by a finance manager at a leading food
manufacturer: 'There is nothing wrong with us issuing commercial paper,
depositing the money in a large lot account and reaping the benefit of the
difference in interest rates.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
