<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / International Company News: BellSouth teams with Telecom on
French network
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS and AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BELLSOUTH, the US tele-communications group, is to co-operate with France
Telecom, the state-owned operator, to build a mobile data transmission
network, worth more than Dollars 80m, in France.
The US group is to take a 12.5 per cent stake in the French company's
recently-created mobile data business, France Telecom Mobiles Data, for an
undisclosed price.
This is the latest of a series of foreign partnerships struck by France
Telecom in the two years since it was given semi-autonomy from the
telecommunications ministry.
But it is believed to be the first time a foreign company has worked with
France Telecom on an important project on its home territory.
The network, which will allow computer data to be sent by portable
telecommunications sets, will be introduced in Paris this year and other
cities in 1994.
The two companies will co-operate on development and marketing and plan
other alliances with equipment makers, software providers and computer
systems groups.
France Telecom and a private operator have been licensed to run two
competing systems, as is already the case in mobile voice telephones.
The data network will use technology by Ericsson, the Swedish group, which
is already in use in the UK, north America, Finland, Norway and Sweden.
BellSouth also announced it would develop a nationwide mobile data network
in the Netherlands, AP-DJ reports.
Initial construction of the system has begun with service expected to be
available in several markets by the end of the year. When the network is
finished in 1994, it will provide in-building coverage in important
commercial centres such as Amsterdam, Rotterdam and The Hague, and
comprehensive mobile coverage in smaller cities and major traffic corridors.
</TEXT>
