<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / International Company News: Eni set to restructure foreign
unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ENI, the state-owned energy and chemicals concern implicated in Italy's
political corruption scandal, plans to rationalise its network of foreign
subsidiaries.
The aim is to improve transparency and accountability at the group, which
had sales of L50,883bn (Dollars 32bn) in 1991 and 209 subsidiaries
registered abroad.
The Eni group comprises the parent company and 12 main subsidiaries, all but
one of which, Eni International Holding, are based in Italy. The biggest
subsidiaries in terms of sales are Snam, involved in gas supply and
distribution; EniChem, Italy's biggest chemicals concern; Agip, the upstream
oil and gas operation; and Agip Petroli, which handles the downstream side
of the oil business.
While Eni International Holding, a purely financial operation, has four
subsidiaries, all abroad, Eni's other big subsidiaries have many of their
operations registered outside Italy.
Agip Petroli and EniChem together have around 60 non-Italian companies,
while Agip has 30 subsidiaries registered abroad. Among the most common
locations are financial centres or tax havens such as Geneva and Jersey.
Details of the streamlining are still vague, but the changes are expected
principally to affect the Eni group's financial subsidiaries or holding
companies, rather than trading or sales operations.
Eni has become a focal point for investigations into political corruption
and illegal financing of Italy's main political parties.
Illegal payments to politicians and kickbacks on big contracts have
allegedly been channeled through Eni's foreign operations.
</TEXT>
