<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / International Company News: Hoechst declines 7% in first
quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PROFITS at Hoechst, the German chemicals group, have fallen by around 7 per
cent in the first quarter of the current year, Mr Jurgen Dormann, finance
director, said yesterday.
The year had got off to a 'miserable' start and there was no sign of
improvement, according to Mr Wolfgang Hilger, group chairman. Price
pressures had increased, and there were now fears that volume sales would be
hit by falling demand.
The continuing decline in Hoechst's profits, following a 17.7 per cent
pre-tax fall during the whole of 1992, and a 26 per cent slump in the first
three months of last year, would force the group to make further savings, he
added.
'This has become the bitter truth, not only in chemicals but in other
important sectors,' Mr Dormann said.
Uneconomic plant would be shut and the German workforce, reduced by 4,100
last year to 81,000 would fall further. Some 3,000 places would go at the
parent, reducing the payroll there to 50,000.
Around 3,900 people were currently working on short-time in Germany and they
would be joined next month by a 500 PVC film workers.
Although Mr Dormann gave no details, he said the German business, which
accounts for almost half of group turnover, had been hit especially hard in
the first quarter.
Pharmaceuticals sales had fallen 17 per cent in the first two months, under
pressure from health spending cuts.
Mr Hilger added that while the group's overall foreign turnover fell 2 per
cent in January and February, domestic business had declined by an
'alarming' 15 per cent, resulting in a 5 per cent decline to DM7bn. Sales
had fallen in all sectors.
The company spent DM770m during 1992 on restructuring, of which DM565m went
on job reductions.
</TEXT>
