<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / International Company News: Hypo-Bank surges to DM1.5bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BAYERISCHE Hypothe-ken-und Wechsel-Bank, one of Germany's two large
Bavaria-based banks, yesterday became the third of Germany's 'big five'
banks to announce a large leap in 1992 profits.
Group partial operating profits - which exclude a contribution from
own-account trading - rose by 21.2 per cent to DM1.5bn (Dollars 920m) over
the year. Total operating profits, including DM89.2m earnings in own-account
trading, were up 16.3 per cent to DM1.6bn.
The Bayerische Vereinsbank, the other large Bavarian bank, last week
announced a 24 per cent increase in 1992 partial operating profits to
DM1.48bn, and on Monday the Commerzbank, Germany's third-biggest bank,
reported a 53 per cent surge in group net profits.
The headline profits figures do not reflect a sharp deterioration in credit
risks in the last few months of 1991. Hypo-Bank said it was increasing its
provisions for bad and doubtful debts by 48 per cent, from DM620m in 1991 to
DM917.4m. Earlier this week, the Bayerische Vereinsbank increased its
provisions against domestic commercial debt by 38 per cent to DM860m.
Commerzbank said it would be making substantial provisions against bad and
doubtful debts, details of which will be released on Friday. Dresdner Bank
and Deutsche Bank, Germany's two biggest banks, report next week.
Mr Eberhard Martini, Hypo-Bank's chief executive, said there had been a
'healthy single-digit percentage rise' in general banking and mortgage
banking in the first two months of the year.
</TEXT>
