<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / International Company News: Dresdner Bank plans DM1.2bn
issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DRESDNER BANK, Germany's second-biggest bank, is planning to take advantage
of the sharp rise in its share price this year to make a big rights issue in
the next few weeks. The two-for-19 issue is expected to raise between
DM1.2bn (Dollars 732m) and DM1.6bn.
The bank, which next week is expected to report double-digit profit growth
for 1992, gave no details on the purpose of the capital-raising measure, one
of the largest rights issues ever undertaken by a German company.
It said proceeds of the issue would be used to finance growth. The cash was
not needed to meet capital adequacy guidelines, and it ruled out using it to
buy shares in the Banque Nationale de Paris (BNP) to accompany's Dresdner's
co-operation with the state-owned French bank. The agreement is likely to be
cemented with a 10 per cent share swap.
Dresdner intends to issue 4m new shares before its annual meeting on May 14.
Further details will be disclosed only after the bank's supervisory board
meets on Monday, but analysts are predicting a price of around DM350 per
share. The shares closed down DM6.30 at DM399.20 yesterday.
The bank's shares have outperformed the rising DAX-30 index over the year,
rising nearly 13 per cent, compared to a market increase of 6.7 per cent.
This reflects investors' hopes about the impact of lower interest rates on
the bank's performance and expectations of a sharp rise in 1992 operating
profits.
In December, the bank reported partial operating profits, excluding
own-account trading results, up by nearly 19 per cent to DM2.09bn. The
figure for the full year is expected to exceed DM2.5bn, up from DM2.21bn in
1991.
Dresdner has not given any growth predictions for the current year. Growth
in business volume actually fell at the parent company in the first 10
months of the year, reflecting the bank's cautious approach to new lending
in Germany's worsening credit environment.
The rights issue will rank with Daimler-Benz's DM1.95bn issue in 1989 and
RWE's DM1.64bn issue this year as one of Germany's largest ever.
</TEXT>
