<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Minorco makes Pounds 55m Spanish
acquisition from Redland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR and KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINORCO, the overseas investment arm of the Anglo American Corporation of
South Africa, has agreed to pay Pounds 55m to acquire a Spanish aggregates
and concrete business from Redland, the UK building materials group.
The deal marks a further expansion of Minorco's growing European quarries
operations.
It is buying Steetley Iberia, purchased last year by Redland when it
acquired the Steetley group in a contested takeover bid worth Pounds 613m.
The Spanish business, comprising 14 quarries and gravel pits and 21 ready
mix concrete plants, is the leading supplier or aggregates and concrete to
the Madrid market.
The sale price constitutes an exit p/e of almost 18 on profits of Pounds 5m
last year, assuming a 38 per cent tax charge. Spanish construction output,
however, is forecast to fall by up to 4 per cent this year.
Profits of Steetley Iberia could slip to between Pounds 2m and Pounds 3m
this year, putting the sale on a prospective exit p/e of about 30. In that
case Redland would have received a good price for the business, said
analysts.
Minorco has built up its European quarries business from a standing start
two years ago beginning with with acquisition of Elbekies in the former east
Germany for Dollars 108m. This was followed by the purchase of the Lausitzer
hardstone quarry business, also near Berlin, for Dollars 17m. In the UK
Minorco paid Dollars 207m to ICI for Buxton Lime Industries.
Mr John Draper, who recently took over as managing director of the
industrial minerals division, said the company had every intention of adding
more acquisitions and more countries to its European business.
In the six months to December 31, these reported operating profits of
Dollars 23m (Pounds 16m) on sales totalling Dollars 75m.
Redland, which announces its 1992 results on Thursday, has raised more than
Pounds 150m from disposals since the autumn, including more than Pounds 90m
from former Steetley businesses. Despite this, gearing is still thought to
be between 55 per cent and 60 per cent after the sale to Minorco.
Redland said that Steetley had originally bought the Spanish operations for
more than Pounds 80m but that had subsequently been written down to Pounds
55m in Redland's books.
</TEXT>
