<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Polypipe advances to Pounds 6.4m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLYPIPE, the Doncaster-based manufacturer of industrial and commercial
plastic pipes and fittings, reported a 9.5 per cent increase in interim
pre-tax profits, from Pounds 5.85m to Pounds 6.4m.
Turnover in the six months to December 31 increased by 7.4 per cent to
Pounds 49.2m (Pounds 45.8m) and included a full contribution from Aquapipes
and GCA Windows, both acquired in October 1991.
Together the two businesses contributed more than Pounds 2m to turnover and
about Pounds 150,000 to profits.
Earnings per share rose 9.4 per cent to 2.78p (2.54p) and the interim
dividend is raised to 0.66p (0.63p).
Mr Kevin McDonald, chairman, said the results reflected the continuing
strength of the core plastic pipe and fittings business, which accounted for
Pounds 32.4m (Pounds 30.2m) of sales, and the development and successful
integration of more recently acquired domestic plastic product activities.
Polypipe and Paragon increased their share of the above-ground rainwater,
soil and waste market as did Derwent MacDee in the market for flushing
cisterns, toilet and other bathroom fittings.
Capital expenditure during the first half totalled Pounds 4.96m and will be
about the same level in the second half when new machinery to produce large
diameter twin-wall pipes comes on stream.
The balance sheet remains strong with no net debt.
COMMENT
Polypipe continues to buck the recession helped by some astute acquisitions
including Aquapipes whose lightweight twin-walled corrugated pipes use 40
per cent less raw material than their solid counterparts and are set to
gradually replace clay and concrete. Only 12.5 per cent of the group's
business is related to new housing with the the bulk coming from the much
less sensitive repair, maintenance and improvement markets where new
products are helping margins. The group has so far resisted pressure from
its raw material suppliers to pass on price increases, which might not stick
anyway. Given the seasonally-stronger second half has already shown some
signs of improvement, full year pre-tax profits of Pounds 17m look
reasonable. However, the shares have climbed sharply in the last six months
and at yesterday's close of 137p now trade on a lofty multiple of over 18
and look fully valued.
</TEXT>
