<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Bowater ahead 49% in line with rights issue
forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOWATER, the packaging and industrial films company, yesterday announced
profits in line with its own forecast, and will pay a second interim
dividend rather than a final as a way of beating Budget changes.
Pre-tax profits for the year to December 31 were Pounds 147.2m, a 49 per
cent increase on 1991, as forecast last month when the company launched a
Pounds 295m rights issue to fund its acquisition of Specialty Coatings
International, the US coatings company.
Turnover improved from Pounds 1.27bn to Pounds 1.57bn, again in line with
expectations, and the operating profit margin rose to 9 per cent against 8.6
per cent.
Bowater's shares closed unchanged at 490p as the company announced it would
pay shareholders a 'second interim' dividend of 6.65p in place of a final.
The pay-out will be made on April 2 to take advantage of the existing tax
credit of 25 per cent.
Mr Norman Lamont announced in last week's Budget that investors' tax credit
on dividends would fall to 20 per cent from the start of the next financial
year on April 6.
If Bowater had waited to get shareholder approval at the annual meeting in
May to pay the final dividend in June, it would have cost the company about
Pounds 1m more to fund the same distribution.
The total dividend for the year is 11.5p (11p), payable from earnings per
share ahead 12.5 per cent to 25.2p.
'The financial results are commendable when compared with UK plc' commented
Mr Norman Ireland, chairman.
'The overall improvement in earnings in the last quarter of 1992 and into
January 1993 reported in the rights issue document has continued into
February.
'We remain cautious on the out-turn for 1993 but Bowater remains ready to
move wherever the upturn in the business is sighted.'
Mr David Lyon, chief executive, said he was particularly pleased that it had
been able to integrate DRG and Cope Allman, the two companies it bought in
March last year for Pounds 444m, so quickly.
Together, they contributed Pounds 338m to turnover, which had exceeded the
company's expectations.
Bowater said its business in the UK had remained steady, although it had
shown some decline in continental Europe, especially in Germany.
The US had been showing signs of recovery for the last 18 months, and
Australia was also showing signs of an upturn.
COMMENT
Bowater is a very different group from the one the present management came
to in 1987. The City has been impressed by the speed with which it has
realised its goals, first of focusing the company on its core businesses,
and then achieving through acquisitions a 'critical mass' in the added-value
areas of health care packaging, personal care packaging and coated
industrial films. Now the challenge is to develop the synergies between
divisions and harness the potential of a group spread over a large
geographical area and with a wide range of expertise. Judging by its
performance to date, the management is up to the task. Pre-tax profits this
year are forecast at about Pounds 195m, and the shares, on a prospective
multiple of 17.5, look a good long-term buy.
</TEXT>
