<TEXT>
Britain's unpopular chancellor of the exchequer has been called a lot of
things in his time, but this must be the first time he's been christened
Norman, the 'driller killer'.
North Sea oil companies, livid about the chancellor's plans to abolish tax
allowances for exploration work, are moaning that it will quadruple the
costs of looking for oil. But so far only Amerada Hess boss Sam Laidlaw,
whose company stands to lose more than most, has come up with a printable
