<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Observer: Diplomatic choice
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
There are signs of quiet satisfaction in London over news that Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's foreign policy adviser, Peter Hartmann, is pretty certain to
be the next German ambassador - but not because he will be even more
anglophile than his predecessor.
Far more the gentlemanly diplomat than Horst Teltschik, the acute political
operator who previously inhabited the position within the chancellor's
office, Hartmann has been careful to maintain good relations with Downing
Street. Indeed his courteous contacts have underpinned the good personal
chemistry between the chancellor and John Major, which has stood up
remarkably well to the UK government's strange antics over the Maastricht
treaty.
But his winning point is not as a London-lover but rather as an intermediary
who so obviously enjoys the chancellor's confidence, in contrast with
Hermann von Richthofen, the present ambassador, whose diplomatic mildness
has not always found favour with Kohl.
In London since December 1988, von Richthofen still has no definite job
lined up in Bonn, though the German foreign ministry insists his return is
wholly unconnected with the embarrassing decision to publish a letter from
Bundesbank president Helmut Schlesinger shortly after the rout of sterling
last September. The elegant incumbent, a superb dinner host, went down a
treat in his own way. But back home, the anglophilia was viewed with
suspicion. Hence there are those who think a more sceptical character could
carry greater weight.
</TEXT>
