<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Leading Article: Police service
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH Clarke, the home secretary, yesterday announced details of his
plans to reform the police service in England and Wales to improve its
efficiency and effectiveness. As with other government reforms of public
services, local managers - in this case chief constables - will be given
much greater freedom to manage. At the same time, the police authorities to
which chief constables are accountable will be overhauled to make them 'more
powerful and businesslike'.
To achieve this latter aim, Mr Clarke proposes to reduce the number of
elected representatives on the 43 police authorities from two-thirds of the
places to half. The balance will be allocated to local magistrates and Home
Office-appointed business executives. The chairman of each police authority
will be nominated by the home secretary, rather than being elected by the
members.
This will certainly make the chairman more powerful. But it will dilute the
power of locally-elected representatives over the police service. In effect,
the police service will be run by 43 quangos, with weak local control and
strong direction - through the appointment of the chairman - from Whitehall.
This is a recipe for the sort of divided managerial and public
accountability which was responsible for the recent debacle over
computerising the London Ambulance Service.
The dilution of accountability could also make it harder to improve the
effectiveness of policing if it weakens public confidence in the police.
That confidence is essential to encourage the flow of information from the
public which is needed to prevent crime and catch criminals. Restoring it
needs better community relationships and more sensitive policing practices,
neither likely to be fostered by a quango largely beholden to the home
secretary.
Apart from this change in the composition of police authorities, much of the
rest of Mr Clarke's programme is commendable. Chief constables are to be
freed from Home Office controls over manpower levels and capital
expenditure, leaving them to decide what resources are needed according to
local preferences and objectives. Performance indicators are to be published
for police forces to show how successful each is in solving crime, meeting
targets for answering emergency 999 telephone calls and responding to urgent
incidents. And a police authority is to be created for London where up till
now the police have been accountable only to the home secretary.
Mr Clarke has also sensibly drawn back from leaked plans to amalgamate the
43 forces into 25 or fewer. There is no evidence that larger forces are more
successful in solving crime. If mergers are necessary for some forces, they
should be postponed until plans for the reorganisation of local government
by Sir John Banham's Local Government Commission are ready. Meanwhile, the
government should think again before weakening the local accountability of
police authorities.
</TEXT>
<XX>
