<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Leading Article: Kenya's crisis
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
IN DECIDING this week to reverse economic reforms introduced in February,
President Daniel arap Moi has taken a step as impractical as it is
dangerous. His move stems from his frustration over conditions attached to
aid, rather than a considered appraisal of the country's options. The
reforms that donors are urging on Kenya are far from easy, but the
consequences of Mr Moi's retreat into an economic laager will prove more
painful.
The retreat is motivated in part by the impact of adjustment on the system
of patronage and corruption that permeates the government. Transparency and
accountability, the key donor principles, make the life of top government
officials more difficult. What is now at stake, however, is not only the
stability of Kenya. Mr Moi's action poses an uncomfortable challenge for
those western governments and institutions that endorsed the president's
controversial election victory last December.
If Mr Moi had been fairly elected and presided over a sound administration,
he would deserve a sympathetic hearing when he complains of having to
implement 'dictatorial' IMF policies. But there is every reason to fear that
this is not the case. If the IMF's post-election assessments of Kenya's
performance reveal serious economic mismanagement which allowed state funds
to reach party coffers and helped to buy electoral success, Mr Moi's plea
would lose its credibility.
The president now faces a volatile period: a plunging exchange rate and no
recourse to foreign aid; a rapidly rising rate of inflation; high
unemployment; and growing resentment over corruption. As ex-president
Kenneth Kaunda of Zambia belatedly discovered, there is no alternative to
reforms backed by the IMF.
It is possible to understand Mr Moi's frustration without endorsing his
action. In November 1991, the donor community suspended most aid
disbursements to Kenya, pending political and economic reform. On the
political front at least, Mr Moi can argue that he has done what the donors
wanted, but has received no tangible benefit. The ban on multi-party
politics was lifted by the end of 1991. A year later Kenya conducted its
first multi-party poll for 26 years.
In the view of some observers, the election process was seriously flawed.
The majority of donor governments, including Britain and the US (as well as
the Commonwealth observer mission) came to a different conclusion: the
elections, while not entirely free and fair, were acceptable.
Had the west refused to endorse last December's poll, it could today advise
Mr Moi that the only way out of his crisis would be to put his party to the
test of a rigorously supervised general election. Since that option is not
available, donors can now do no more than hope that Mr Moi soon comes to
terms with economic realities. They may find themselves having to conclude
that he is the problem, and not, as they hoped last December, part of its
solution.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>KEZ  Kenya, Africa.
