<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Personal View: Return trip to familiar ground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS TOMBS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The original objectives of Britain's privatisation programme were laudable
and to a considerable extent successful. They involved the replacement of
monolithic state monopolies with the forces of the free market, and the
replacement of institutionalised management with the entrepreneurial skills
of private management.
The successes were in those areas where competition was real, such as road
transport, British Aerospace, British Airways and Rolls-Royce. However, the
quite different considerations and results which emerged after telephones,
gas, electricity and water were privatised raise serious doubts about the
prospects for British Rail, which the government remains determined to
include in its privatisation programme.
The doctrine established earlier in the privatisation process did not change
fundamentally to take account of the public utilities' lack of a free market
in their products and their effective monopolies; rather, an economic model
was substituted for the reality of competition. Thus, in the case of
telecommunications, competition was introduced by the development of
alternative providers; the inevitable snail's pace of such developments,
coupled with the oppressive market-power of Telecom, made the
government-appointed industry regulator the residual legatee of the dream.
In a similar way, the gas regulator has had to substitute for the
shortcomings of the chosen organisation, with its inevitable lack of the
assumed mainspring of the process - a free market. Such substitution is
taking place in the water and electricity industries.
Against this background, it is clear that privatisation of the electricity
supply industry was ill-conceived. Attempts to create competition were based
on a flawed organisational structure in which electricity production was
separated from its distribution and sale, except in Scotland. A duopoly of
production was created in England and Wales and nuclear power was retained
in state ownership, but subsidised by the newly liberated companies.
Competition began with a big distortion, made worse by the price mechanism
of the 'power pool' of the producers and their virtual freedom from
regulation.
But this was not the most important shortcoming of the privatisation
process, for the privatised industry has no mechanism for developing a
strategy of plant or fuels for the future. Since that future tends to be 10
years or more, the market process is simply incapable of recognising, much
less dealing with, the problem. Such a strategy vacuum led, inevitably, to
the recent pit-closure proposals which were the result of a 'dash for gas'
driven by market forces, without consideration of the long-term interests of
the industry, the consumer or the nation. The short-term gains were
hypnotic; responsibility for the long term rested nowhere.
To the surprise of no intelligent observer, this vacuum forced the
government back into the role it had so precipitately abandoned. The price
of the competitive pretence of privatisation is the reversion to government
of a responsibility it had sought to escape. Where this leaves the original
objectives of privatisation is an interesting question, and one is forced to
conclude that the government's objectives of management freedom and
competition have been supplanted by the Treasury's desire for financial
rewards.
These problems offer pointers to the difficulty of privatising the railways.
Here we are again offered a hypothetical market, but with a multitude of
supervisory bodies. Experience should suggest that the 'freedom' of
management will be heavily circumscribed by the new bureaucracy and that a
strategic vacuum - and probably a safety vacuum too - will result. Even
worse, from point of view of the Treasury at least, government may find it
has not succeeded in hiving off its national responsibility.
For the passenger, there is little hope of improvement from the combined
efforts of the various constituent bodies - Railtrack, the franchising
authority, the Safety Commission, the operators and so on. Much more likely
is a paralysis of decision and planning, with a built-in system for 'passing
the buck'. Once again, finally, government will find itself the residual
legatee of its reorganisations.
I hope that it will reconsider its proposals. By all means try to introduce
private-sector methods and management into the railways, but do so by means
which leave management in effective control of their industry's future.
Target-setting, management agencies and contracts are the way forward - not
the limited nostrum of yesteryear.
Lord Tombs was chairman of South of Scotland Electricity Board 1974-1977 and
of the Electricity Council for England and Wales 1977-80
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
