FT  24 MAR 93 / Letter: Duty should encourage LPG use in the UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr AIDEN ROE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The European Commission has accepted the case made by the European
Autogas Association and has proposed minimum excise duties on liquid
petroleum gas (LPG) of Ecu50 ecus per thousand litres compared with Ecu337
for leaded petrol, Ecu207 for unleaded and Ecu245 for diesel. These rates
reflect the relative environmental damage caused by the respective fuels. I
offer two examples of good practice which reflect this:
i) In the UK LPG is the only fuel that fork-lift trucks powered by internal
combustion engines are allowed to use when operating in a confined space.
ii) In Tokyo taxis are supplied with factory fitted LPG tanks and gas
carburettors by law. Petrol and diesel engines are not allowed.
In many EC countries - France, Belgium and the Netherlands being the nearest
examples - LPG is the cheapest road fuel available.
Until Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, or his successor, reduces duties on
LPG, in order to encourage its use, it will be difficult not to conclude
that the environmental justification for across-the-board increases in road
fuel duty is being used rather cynically.
Aiden Roe,
18 Sandileigh Avenue,
Withington,
Manchester M20 9LW
</TEXT>
