<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Childcare pays off for the parent: Sony is starting to reap
the benefits of its Hollywood investments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This summer it will be difficult to escape the media blitz for Columbia
Pictures' Last Action Hero, starring Arnold Schwarzenegger. With production
costs of Dollars 55m and another Dollars 20m budgeted for marketing, it is
one of Hollywood's most expensive movies.
At first glance, the figures seem extravagant for Sony of Japan, which has
been criticised for lavish spending since 1989 when it bought Columbia and
TriStar Pictures and formed Sony Pictures Entertainment (SPE) as a new
combined Hollywood studio.
But the amount seems less outlandish given the extent to which SPE's
operating profit will this year help to offset declining profits from Sony's
core consumer electronics business, which has been severely affected by the
global recession. In the quarter to December 31, the Sony group reported a
62 per cent fall in pre-tax profits, to Dollars 405m.
Wall Street's judgment on Sony's Hollywood acquisition has revolved around
three issues - the financial logic of the deal, the degree to which
much-vaunted synergies, or interdependence, could be achieved between the
hardware (consumer electronics) and software (film) sides of the group, and
the ability of Sony to rebuild the Columbia and TriStar studios, which were
battered three years ago by low morale, weak management and a lack of
box-office hits.
After the takeover, industry critics added up Sony's costs in buying CBS
Records in 1988, its Hollywood acquisition and subsequent studio
investments, and concluded that once debt-servicing expenses were deducted
the return on investment would be low. They suggested that it would be at
least five years before Sony would reap benefits from its Hollywood
adventure.
The group's Dollars 7.9bn of entertainment investments included: Dollars 2bn
on buying CBS Records, and Dollars 3.4bn on the Hollywood studios, which
came with Dollars 1.5bn of debt. Sony then injected a further Dollars 1bn of
capital to rebuild the studios and to acquire the film production company
owned by Mr Peter Guber, who became chairman of SPE.
These days the Tokyo-based owners of SPE may be forgiven for smiling at some
of the Wall Street sceptics. In the financial year that will end next
Wednesday the entertainment side of Sony (films, television, music and
electronic publishing) is likely to provide nearly Dollars 900m of operating
profits before depreciation and debt servicing, or about 45 per cent of the
group's worldwide total.
The figures indicate that Sony's entertainment operations appear to be
bailing out its core consumer electronics business. What is more, the
non-electronics side is producing an annual return on investment of about 11
per cent at the operating level, compared with 6 per cent at the end of
Sony's first year in Hollywood.
Mr David Londoner, an entertainment analyst at Wertheim Schroder, the New
York investment bank, says Wall Street's first impression of Sony's
Hollywood acquisition 'was that they overpaid for a company that was limping
along'. The new perception, he adds, 'is that they have gone a long way
toward making a respectable return on investment'.
When it comes to synergy, Mr Guber says: 'What we are really talking about
is a mutuality of interests in products and marketing between the
entertainment and the electronics businesses'. No one in Tokyo, he explains,
'is telling us to synergise'. Instead the aim is to seek ways of marrying
the technology resources on the electronics side of Sony with the
entertainment side in Hollywood, he says. The Schwarzenegger film is merely
the most graphic example of how the two sides of Sony could work together.
The film, released by Columbia Pictures, will be accompanied by a soundtrack
manufactured by Sony Music. Cinemas showing the film will use the Sony-made
digital sound systems that claim to represent a technology advance beyond
Dolby sound systems. Sony will also sell electronic video games based on the
film that will work on Sony products.
Some cinemas will also introduce 'virtual reality' games made by Sony and
based on the movie. Finally, there are plans for the joint marketing of Sony
television sets and VCRs and the film, with electronic shops across the
country showing extracts from the film on Sony products.
The degree to which hardware-software links can produce significant revenues
still remains to be proved, but a senior Sony executive in the US admits
that in profit terms 'over the past year the software has been carrying the
hardware'.
The man most responsible for the turnround is Mr Guber. He presides over two
studios, Dollars 3bn of annual revenues, 20 per cent of total US box-office
market share and a budget of about Dollars 600m for more than 20 movies a
year.
In the financial year now ending, SPE is estimated to have made an operating
profit of more than Dollars 300m from its film and television productions
and cinema chain subsidiaries. That is 22 per cent better than the previous
year and double the profit level of 1989-90, when Sony first bought into
Hollywood. However, despite the improvement, the return on Sony's total
investment of Dollars 4.4bn is just 7 per cent and still short of the return
made on the much cheaper music business.
At Wertheim Schroder, Mr Londoner stresses that SPE still has more work to
do to reach the operating profit levels of studios like Warner and Disney,
both of which earn more than Dollars 400m a year.
In New York, Mr Guber's boss, Mr Mickey Schulhof, the vice-chairman of Sony
USA, the US subsidiary which controls SPE, agrees that Warner and Disney
earn more, but stresses that with a 20 per cent market share, SPE is now
among the top three Hollywood studios. He adds that it is not unreasonable
to expect the entertainment side to achieve a 15 per cent return on
investment within the next couple of years.
Mr Guber used much of the estimated Dollars 1bn of fresh capital over the
past three years to rebuild the two studios, taking on staff and forging
deals with directors and producers. That has meant producing flagship films,
such as last year's Hook, based on the Peter Pan fairytale, which have not
reaped critical praise but which have been box-office hits and helped to
renew confidence in the studios among cinema chains and distributors.
Another top priority was the studio's television division, which last year
generated operating profits of Dollars 175m (see chart), equal to the film
side. The business was restructured, and while its profits will dip next
year because of a cyclical reduction in its earnings from programme
syndication, it is now being expanded internationally. Mr Mel Harris, the
new head of the TV division, is exploring co-production deals with RTL in
Germany and the Berlusconi group in Italy.
Globalisation is as much a buzzword at SPE as it is elsewhere in corporate
America, and Mr Guber says he is increasingly sensitive to non-US markets,
which provide about half of all box-office proceeds. 'We feel the impact
here when England is not doing well and Germany is slipping into recession.'
Mr Guber's senior aides, and especially Mr Jonathan Dolgen, president of the
motion picture division, say they are working hard to trim costs where
possible. 'The cost side has to be managed, but in a way that is not
intrusive into the creative side. No one is going to cut production or
marketing costs in half, but we can make and market some pictures for 5 per
cent less,' Mr Dolgen explains.
Cost-cutting is evident on a visit to the back lots and executive suites of
Sony Pictures. Shooting schedules have been tightened, and editing and
marketing costs have been trimmed. Morale is higher than it was a year ago,
the result of the rebuilding programme, tighter management and box-office
success. It also reflects the growing awareness that Hollywood is bolstering
its Sony parent company back in Tokyo for the first time since the Japanese
entered the business. As one studio executive put it: 'It's nice to feel
that we're needed.'
 -------------------------------------------------------------
Sony Pictures Entertainment: a sharp picture
 -------------------------------------------------------------
