<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Letter: Tailored aid to Russia crucial to success of
transition process
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Dr CHRIS DOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The present situation of the Russian reformers holding a plebiscite
could, if the outcome endorses Mr Yeltsin, result in a considerable increase
in presidential power. A strengthening of the power of the presidential
office has attractions in the present climate but carries the risk of a
military-backed dictatorship if opponents seek to overthrow Mr Yeltsin.
While the strengthening of the presidential office seems the most compelling
short-term remedy to restore the momentum of the Russian reform programme it
is a view that must be held with trepidation because it raises the spectre
of a militarily mismanaged economy. On the other hand, without increased
presidential powers the Russian Federation is likely to disintegrate and
civil disturbances proliferate as the reform programme collapses and
regional differences accelerate; the latter would have global implications.
Confronted with the possibility of political repression and global adverse
consequences the west faces a serious dilemma vis-a-vis its political
support and assistance programmes ('The choice over Russia', March 17). It
has been argued by some, such as presidents Clinton and Mitterrand ('US and
France seek early G7 talks', March 10), that by speedily increasing aid it
will result in support for the reformers. However, increasing short-term
western aid may exacerbate problems, as it is likely to be poorly targeted,
and being a panic like measure it could serve to strengthen the position of
those opposed to Mr Yeltsin who will seize on it as further proof of
Russia's decline under Mr Yeltsin.
The resolution to the problems of Russian transition will rest largely on
internal politics and for this reason short-term financial measures designed
to influence the outcome of the forthcoming plebiscite will at best play a
marginal role. Nevertheless, carefully tailored support of the kind
suggested by Professor Nuti (Letters, March 23) will be crucial in ensuring
the success of transition in Russia.
Chris Doyle,
senior research officer,
Department of Applied
Economics,
University of Cambridge
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9111 Executive Offices.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
