<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Arts: Quartermaine's Terms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALASTAIR MACAULAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Have you seen The Edward Fox Performance? Observed once, it is very
interesting and rather touching. It embodies a classy English eccentric of
terminal affability. He exists in a cocoon apart from everyday communication
and ordinary life. Every main vowel is drawled into a complex diphthong
('upside dahn,' 'smairshing'.) The way he adjusts from one tilting stance to
another is deployed for maximum effect. Each of the half-dozen chief facial
expressions is held for a minimum of five seconds, then contrasted with
another. The mouth, in particular, goes through a range of gaping positions
 -as if posing for Munch.
If he chooses his repertory carefully, he might go on giving this
performance ad infinitum. Alas, the signs are that he intends to do so.
Returning to Simon Gray's Quartermaine's Terms, in whose 1981 West End
premiere and subsequent TV production he enjoyed success, he gives not only
the same performance he did in '81 but also the same as in The
Philanthropist in the West End in 1991 (and before that at Chichester), and
much the same as when he played Higgins in the tour of My Fair Lady last
year.
The first time around, Fox's performance is an icon of Englishness as
marvellous as a Beefeater or a bowler hat. (And the deep furrow down each
cheek is so fascinating that you want it hung in the Tate.) The more you
watch, however, the less there is to see. The same goes, I am sorry to say,
for Quartermaine's Terms. This revival is staged by Kevin Billington, who
directed the tour of the original production; and the cast includes another
actor from the original production and another from the TV version. Almost
everyone gives a flawless performance. Flawless except that the whole affair
now seems too pat, too formulaic.
The trick of Quartermaine's Terms is that it applies farce methods to
produce a comic surface over a situation which continually becomes more and
more pathetic. The situation is a staff room and the lives of its seven
staff members. One running joke is the accident-prone new teacher; another
is the mistakes people make over his name or the title of the play currently
on at the local theatre; another is Quartermaine's mindless
hail-fellow-well-met dazed charm. Others teachers have personal crises and
change from scene to scene. Quartermaine, who alone never changes and
undergoes no crisis, is in fact the most pathetic character of all.
Quartermaine is one of those uncommunicative types who recur in English
literature and drama, from Evelyn Waugh to Harold Pinter, and his apparent
stalemate (actually a helpless decline and fall) is, of course, a deliberate
portrait of English decline in general. Simon Gray handles it all very
entertainingly, but the formula is not a rewarding one to reexamine. In this
revival, Clive Francis, James Grout, Sarah Badel and Lucy Scott contribute
excellent pieces English character acting. Best of all is Peter Barkworth as
Eddie Loomis, the school's fussy, pedantic, and increasingly decrepit
director. His every detail is eloquent, like the way he leans sideways
suspiciously before saying 'Oh good'.
At the Richmond Theatre until March 27
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7922 Theatrical Producers and Services.
