<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Management: Settling down to small talk - Xerox has
undergone sweeping organisational changes in its internal makeup
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Xerox is at it again. The US document processing company, which became a
by-word in the 1980s for its adoption of cutting-edge management theories,
has been undergoing another big upheaval.
A year ago Paul Allaire, its chairman, unveiled a radical redesign of the
company's management structure, or what he calls its 'organisational
architecture', in an attempt to solve one of the central problems facing
large companies everywhere: how to retain the entrepreneurial flair and
flexibility of a small business.
'We are trying to get the benefits of a small company of quickness in time
to market, decision-making and the elimination of bureaucratic activities,'
he says, 'without losing any of the advantages of a big organisation.'
Xerox is hardly alone. US giants ranging from American Telephone &amp; Telegraph
to General Electric have gone through wrenching organisational upheavals
over the past few years in pursuit of this 1990s Holy Grail.
And International Business Machines also unveiled a scheme similar to
Xerox's last year.
But Xerox offers some distinctive lessons, partly because of the revolution
it went through in the 1980s and partly because of the way it has approached
its make-over, seeking to change not just the outward architecture of the
company but its internal culture too.
Xerox invented the plain paper copier in 1959 and became one of the fastest
growing companies in the US.
But then a combination of complacency, anti-trust problems and executive
infighting allowed Japanese rivals to make large inroads in its market
share.
But the company fought back in the 1980s under the then chairman, David
Kearns, and became one the few US businesses to win back market share from
the Japanese. This was due in large measure to its embrace of total quality
management, which involves a business committing itself to the highest
quality in everything it does and making customer satisfaction its number
one goal.
But while total quality management can dramatically improve the performance
of a business, it is no guarantee of continued success.
Allaire, a 26-year veteran of Xerox who took over as chief executive in
1990, decided that the company needed a complete redesign of its structure.
However, he emphasises that his shake-up is not a break with the Kearns era,
but builds on the company's past quality achievements: 'If David had still
been here, we would probably have to do the same kinds of changes,' he says.
The re-design also owes much to Xerox's long-standing practice of
benchmarking, or comparing its organisation and performance with those of
other well-managed businesses.
Before implementing its reforms it took a close look at AT&amp;T, Corning and
Alcoa, which had previously introduced 'act small' restructurings.
Xerox was advised by David Nadler, a prominent management consultant, who
helped steer the company through its total quality transformation in 1980s
and who also acts as an adviser to AT&amp;T and Corning.
Its shake-up stems in large part from sweeping change in the office
equipment business, where digital technology, which allows images to be
captured electronically, is replacing traditional light-lens technology.
This means that the stand-alone copier is becoming part of the much larger
information technology business - a device which can form part of an
electronic information network and can incorporate a variety of additional
functions, including fax, full-colour printing and the scanning of documents
to put them in digital form.
That, in turn, is likely to bring new competitors into the industry from the
computer field and force out some of the less efficient traditional copier
manufacturers.
Allaire insists that for Xerox this is much more an opportunity than a
threat. But it means the company needs to be more responsive to changing
customer needs and keep on the leading edge of technology, and he believes
its old structure was ill-equipped for this.
The document processing business, with some Dollars 14bn (Pounds 9.8bn) in
annual sales, was organised as a classic monolithic company, divided into
departments such as sales and manufacturing and with a large central staff.
But this, he says, means that, 'people get too accustomed to sitting on
their hands and waiting for a decision to come down from above'.
Under the new system, Xerox consists of nine separate stand-alone
businesses, each organised around particular products and markets and each
with total responsibility for their profit and loss account.
Allaire likes to describe this as turning the traditional, vertically
organised business on its side: at one end, there is an integrated research
and development arm, which feeds ideas into the nine businesses.
These in turn supply products to a unified customer operations division,
which sells, installs and services equipment and is organised by geographic
region.
The sales force was not divided up among the nine businesses because Xerox
felt it important to keep a single face to the customer, and did not want to
run the risk of salespeople from different operations competing with each
other.
Wayland Hicks, executive president, operations, insists this arrangement has
not diluted the financial accountability of the nine operations. 'We have
broken up the financial system so the business heads have a clear idea of
what their sales costs are, and they work very closely with the operating
people.'
The new system also ties Xerox's Palo Alto Research Centre (Parc) more
closely into the business. During the past 20 years, the Parc has made some
of the most important inventions in information technology, including the
personal computer and laser printer, but Xerox repeatedly failed to
capitalise commercially on its ideas, allowing rival companies to do so.
Sceptics still wonder whether the company will speed up its notorious
tardiness in bringing products to market. But Hicks says there is some early
evidence that the new structure is helping.
For example, two variants of one of its machines were recently brought to
market in a time 'unheard of under the previous organisation,' thanks to 'a
management team that saw a market-place need and was able to make and
implement decisions in a way which involved a lot fewer people and fewer
levels of the organisation'.
However, Allaire points out that changing the formal structure of an
organisation is the easiest part of architectural change. Two other vital
elements are harder to engineer: getting people with the right skills in the
right place and changing the organisation's 'software', its informal network
of relationships and culture.
Xerox discovered it had a dearth of general managers a few rungs down the
corporate hierarchy - just at the point where these were now critical to
success. Previously people at this level tended to be specialists, lacking
all-round management skills.
As for culture, Allaire was anxious for the new businesses to keep in mind
the needs of the group as a whole, since much of Xerox's strength comes from
its combined technological and global marketing abilities.
One important way of doing so was to change the pay system. The bonuses of
middle managers are now based on an arithmetic calculation which multiplies
the achievements of their part of the business with that of the group,
rather than just adding the components together. Multiplication makes the
group's performance far more critical to the size of the individual's bonus.
A year into the new world, Allaire says he's 'pleased with progress. We're
on track, though if you talk to a number of people they'd say it's tougher
to do than they thought.'
The company has also just announced plans to sell off its poorly performing
financial services businesses, which were acquired in the early 1980s to
shore up the copier business.
It is too early to say how much of a lift all these initiatives will give to
the company's financial performance, although Wall Street is reasonably
impressed by the shape of the business. Its product range is strong relative
to its rivals, and its 1992 results showed a 12 per cent increase in
document processing income, despite the weak global economy.
There is, however, no room for complacency. Xerox, says Allaire, will 'have
to change more in the next five years than we have in the past 10. We cannot
sit back on our laurels'.
</TEXT>
