FT  24 MAR 93 / People: Mercury Asset Management
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
One member of the government's National Advisory Council for Education and
Training Targets, a high-powered committee unveiled last week, is Carol
Galley (right), one of the City's most successful female fund managers.
Galley, deputy chairman of Mercury Asset Management, points out that, given
her close involvement in investment decisions, it would be inappropriate for
her to sit on the board of a company. But she says she has agreed to work
for Nacett not only because she believes generally in the importance of
vocational training to the success of British industry but because of her
faith in the abilities of Peter Davis, chief executive of Reed Elsevier and
of Post Office chairman Michael Heron, the council's chairman and vice
chairman respectively.
'I have observed them in the corporate sector. If anyone has a chance of
making something like this work, it is these people,' she reckons.
She joined Warburg Investment Management as a librarian in 1971 straight
from university.
