<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / Granada buys caterer from P&amp;O: Sutcliffe included in Pounds
360m sale of groups with Pounds 500m sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GRANADA, the television and leisure group, is increasing its business
services activities with the Pounds 360m acquisition of catering, work wear
and other companies from P&amp;O.
Sutcliffe, the largest company being acquired, is the third largest contract
caterer in the UK behind Compass Group and Gardner Merchant. For Mr Gerry
Robinson, who joined Granada as chief executive in 1991 from Compass, the
purchase takes Granada into contract catering and gives opportunities to
save money through joint purchasing with Granada's motorway catering
business.
'It's an excellent strategic fit,' Mr Robinson said. 'My own knowledge of
catering also makes it a very safe affair,' he said.
The other companies being acquired include Spring Grove, the UK's third
largest textile rental operator. P&amp;O chairman Lord Sterling said all the
businesses being sold were UK based and the money would develop P&amp;O's
international business.
The companies being sold had combined turnover last year of Pounds 500m and
made trading profits of Pounds 29m. Sutcliffe had trading profits of Pounds
15.2m on turnover of Pounds 358m. It had more than 2,000 contracts, of which
more than 90 per cent were on a 'cost plus' basis. Sutcliffe's operating
margins of 4.3 per cent compared with about 10 per cent for Compass, Mr
Robinson said. The acquisitions would be 'at least' earnings neutral this
year.
Granada hoped to improve margins in Sutcliffe and Spring Grove by improved
purchasing and control of overheads.
Following the acquisition, Granada's TV rental division would account for
less than 50 per cent of trading profits for the first time for 'many
years', the company said.
Granada will use Pounds 212m of existing resources, and is raising a further
Pounds 148m through a vendor placing to institutions at 350p a share. The
issue was well received by the stock market, where the shares gained 20p to
385p. The placing was underwritten by Hoare Govett and Swiss Bank
Corporation.
Borrowings for the deal will increase Granada's net debt to Pounds 350m,
equal to gearing of more than 80 per cent. Mr Henry Staunton, finance
director, said gearing would fall to about 50 per cent next year.
Lex, Page 22; P&amp;O results, Page 24
