<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 93 / The Lex Column: Prudential
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Mick Newmarch has spent the best part of three years clearing dead wood
at the Prudential. Even Mercantile and General, the reinsurance business
which blighted yesterday's figures, has been chopped down to size since the
year-end. Earnings growth from here on may depend on the core life and
pensions business. It remains an open question whether Mr Newmarch will
prove as adept at delivering organic growth.
But the Pru may now be inclined to look at acquisitions. Its stubborn
refusal to reveal the state of its balance sheet yesterday - hardly the
standard of disclosure one might expect from a large institutional investor
 -suggests an unusual degree of sensitivity. Still, the Pru is right that a
conventional balance sheet would ignore the value of its life fund. Making
an acquisition through the fund could be one way of unlocking that value for
shareholders.
