FT  24 MAR 93 / The Lex Column: Granada Group
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Granada's shares may have rebounded strongly but they were always likely to
flatten out as the market began to worry about the group's continuing growth
prospects. The acquisition of Sutcliffe catering group may neatly solve the
dilemma.
A price tag of Pounds 360m, representing an exit multiple of 18, hardly
looks excessive for a company with expansion opportunities. Although the
acquisition may only be earnings neutral in its first year it should boost
profits thereafter.
Granada should gain advantages from joint buying with its motorway services
division. It can also apply its proven cost-cutting skills to improving
Sutcliffe's somewhat meagre margins. Even so, P&amp;O sold because it feared UK
catering was bound to face increasingly tough competition from international
competitors. So Granada has some hard pounding ahead.
