<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Sixteen arrested after clashes with police outside Timex
plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S worst picket line violence for seven years erupted yesterday
outside the Timex plant in Dundee as an increasingly bitter strike entered
its fifth week.
Sixteen people were arrested when up to 600 demonstrators battled with
police as replacement workers were taken by bus through picket lines into
the plant, which makes printed circuit boards.
Angry strike supporters sat down in front of the gates to try to stop the
bus. Some union officials accused the police of over-reacting and losing
control. Timex last night deplored the violence and said the demonstrators
were trying to intimidate its workforce.
The dispute is rapidly becoming a cause celebre in Scotland. Last Saturday,
more than 7,000 people marched through Dundee in support of the striking
workers, who were dismissed for refusing to accept cuts in benefits. The
sackings went ahead despite the fact that the workers had agreed to return
under protest.
More and more supporters from organisations including Militant Tendency and
the Socialist Workers' party are turning up at Timex to demonstrate their
solidarity with the strikers.
Britain has not witnessed such violent scenes in an industrial dispute since
the 1986 siege of News International's plant at Wapping in east London by
print workers. Mr Gavin Laird, general secretary of the AEEU engineering
union, said yesterday his union had become 'ensnared in the draconian labour
laws that did not help to solve industrial disputes'. He added the AEEU was
ready at any time to talk with Timex about the dispute and prepared to use
the Advisory Conciliation and Arbitration Service to settle the strike.
Yesterday's escalation in the dispute followed the legal victory gained by
the AEEU in the Court of Session in Edinburgh last Friday, when Timex failed
to secure the extension of an existing interdict - or injunction - which
would have banned all meetings, marches and demonstrations held by the union
within 50 yards of the plant. Timex was also ordered to pay the union's
legal costs. Union officials believe the company has already spent up to
Pounds 70,000 in legal expenses since the dispute began.
On Friday, a further confrontation will take place in the Court of Session
when the AEEU will appeal against the original injunction secured by the
company to limit pickets to six at the main gate. Union officials claim the
strike is having a severe impact on Timex's business.
The US-owned company has recruited up to 190 workers to replace the 320 it
dismissed but the AEEU said yesterday the newcomers were not skilled enough
to do their jobs.
Violent search for Dundee settlement, Page 13
</TEXT>
