<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Foreign bidders seek phone deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO OVERSEAS companies are among the four shortlisted to take over the
telecommunications system linking government offices across Britain when it
is privatised this year.
OTC Australia, the international arm of Australia's state-owned
telecommunications carrier, and Sprint, which is the third-largest
long-distance carrier in the US, are bidding against British Telecom and
Mercury for the three-year contract.
The contract, worth about Pounds 11m a year, is to operate the 13 switch
centres and subsidiary centres linking about 250,000 officials in 1,000
government office locations.
The Government Telecommunications Network, with assets of about Pounds 10m,
handles more than 66m calls a year.
It is served by the Government Centre for Information Systems, an in-house
concern. The long-distance part of its business is being privatised under
the government's market-testing policy.
Although the trunk lines linking the locations are leased from BT or
Mercury, the foreign suppliers see the contract as an opportunity to
establish a presence in the UK telecommunications market, and a vantage
point from which to exploit the European market, which is gradually being
liberalised.
OTC Australia is also applying to the Department of Trade and Industry for
an international simple resale licence, under a competition regime for
international calls established at the end of last year. The licence would
enable OTC to lease international circuits and resell services.
If OTC gains the licence it is likely to seek to undercut BT tariffs for
calls to Australia. OTC's goal is to build Pounds 1bn of business outside
Australia in the next five years.
In the past two years it has lost a tenth of its domestic business in the
newly liberalised Australian market to carriers including BT and Cable and
Wireless, which owns Mercury.
Sprint, which is similarly anxious to break into the European market, has
applications pending with the DTI for licenses to provide local, trunk and
international services on its own network.
</TEXT>
