<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Dreams of privatisation: The restructuring of the German
steel industry as part of the upheaval in the sector throughout Europe has
elicited widespread protest. FT writers report on the hopes and fears of two
communities in east and west Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   EISENHUTTENSTADT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE workers at Ekostahl, Eisenhuttenstadt, reckon they have done their bit
in reducing the workforce and capacity. 'There are only 5,000 people now
working here,' says Mr Gunther Reski, head of the plant's workers' council.
'But in practice, only 3,500 have full-time jobs. The rest are part-time, on
training, or else are on job creation schemes. Before 1990, 11,000 people
were employed here.'
Ekostahl, 100km east of Berlin and near the Polish border, was built by the
former East German communist regime in 1951. The 50,000 inhabitants of
Eisenhuttenstadt, an annex of the giant steel mill, are dependent on the
plant, which used to buy iron ore from Russia and sold its finished products
back to the former Soviet Union and eastern Europe.
'We were producing over 2.1m tons a year. We've brought production down to
900,000 tons. Now we are looking for a break,' says Mr Reski, a 51-year-old
steelworker who has spent the past 30 years with Ekostahl.
The workers are pinning their hopes on an ambitious plan that would
eventually result in the privatisation of parts of the company. The first
phase, already agreed in principle by their owner, the Treuhand - the agency
responsible for privatising the east German economy - entails modernisation
of the cold steel works, for DM310m (Pounds 131m). The second phase would
turn Ekostahl into a mini-mill, inspired by the highly successful Nucor
plant in North Carolina. That would require an additional DM750m.
The workers are waiting anxiously for a decision on the aid package. But
they are also hoping that IG Metall, Germany's giant engineering trade
union, will not press for a strike at the plant.
'A strike is the last thing we need,' says Harold, a 32-year-old Ekostahl
employee. 'IG Metall wants a 26 per cent wage increase to equalise wages
between eastern and western German workers. But if that means a strike, I
would opt for a job, not a higher wage. Many of my friends think the same.'
Eisenhuttenstadters also worry about a strike, due on April 1 after IG
Metall has balloted its members. 'We can't afford strikes, because the
workers will lose money. We can't afford strikes, because it might deter
buyers for Ekostahl,' says Britta, who has recently set up her own food
shop.
Local IG Metall officials, and owners of new, small businesses, are aware of
the dilemma. Job security is vital for their future, and the town's. They
explain how the 36 ancillary work shops formerly owned by Ekostahl have been
privatised, and are surviving. Mr Kurt Rakoczi, manager of a local insurance
company, says if Ekostahl does not get the go-ahead for modernisation, the
town, and the fledgling privatised sector, would die.
They have already set up a solidarity fund for unemployed workers. 'We are
still prepared to make sacrifices for Ekostahl because we believe the
mini-mill could work here,' says Mr Reski. 'What is the alternative?'
</TEXT>
<XX>
