<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Legal threat ends blockade of port
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FLOTILLA of fishing boats from north-east England blockaded one of
Britain's biggest ports yesterday to publicise fishermen's opposition to the
government's fisheries policy.
The 8-hour blockade, from dawn, of the mouth of the River Tees disrupted
shipping movements in and out of the Port of Tees and Hartlepool. It delayed
10 vessels, including two carriers exporting Sunderland-made Nissan cars.
The protest was called off after threats of legal action against the
fishermen from the Port of Tees and Hartlepool Authority. As they sailed
away the men warned of more action, at unspecified locations, this week,
despite fisheries minister Mr David Curry's condemnation of the protest as
'a waste of time' which would not influence government policy.
Yesterday's action by men from ports from North Shields to Scarborough was
organised by the National Federation of Fishermen's Organisations, which
represents most fishermen in England and Wales.
NFFO chief executive Mr Richard Banks joined the blockade on board the
Whitby trawler Sarb J. He highlighted two main objectives of the protest.
One was to press for import controls, particularly on cheap Russian fish
entering Britain. Fishermen claim that Russian cod is entering the UK at
roughly half the minimum EC price.
The second aim is to force the government to abandon the new Sea Fish
Conservation Act which will restrict the number of days British fishermen
can go to sea. Mr Banks claimed the act would cut up to 30 days off the
average total that fishermen work at present. He said this was equivalent to
a 10 per cent or Pounds 2,000 drop in annual income.
The decision to disrupt shipping had not been taken lightly, he added. 'We
want to bring to everybody's attention we are in dire straits,' he said. The
fishermen also called for more advertising of fish and immediate
implementation of the EC's payment scheme for decommissioning fishing
vessels.
Mr Curry is tomorrow meeting the NFFO and the fish processors, who depend
heavily on imports. Responding to Mr Banks' comments, he said British
fishermen must accept the need to take action to conserve stocks.
Mr Curry said the industry's problems included insufficient consumer demand
for fish and large landings by British fishermen, glutting the marketplace.
'The whole problems of the industry can't all be blamed on other people,' he
said.
Last week's Brussels meeting of the European Council of Fisheries Ministers
had, he said, ruled out a blanket ban on non-EC imports. The protectionism
wanted by the protesting fishermen contradicted moves towards liberalising
trade.
Shipowners and agents using Teesport expressed concern at the protest. 'I'm
very disappointed the fishermen should take an illegal step,' said Mr Derek
Munt, managing director of ferry owner Ferrymasters. The departure of the
company's MV Elk was delayed. Two of the 10 vessels affected yesterday were
diverted to Hull.
</TEXT>
