<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Clark board decides on bidder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BOARD of C&amp;J Clark last night decided to recommend one of three
potential bidders for the family-owned shoe manufacturer after a marathon
meeting lasting almost 12 hours.
The board convened at 10.30am, but by early evening had still not chosen
between the three rivals: property and commodities group Berisford; shoe
manufacturer FII and an investment consortium of existing shareholders
backed by Electra Investment Trust.
Although the decision is not expected to be announced until after
shareholders have been informed, speculation centred on the success of the
investment consortium. As Clark shareholders, the institutions have
pre-emptive rights over the sale of its shares.
The board is believed to have rejected a fourth bid in cash or shares from a
group of institutions which was pitched at approximately Pounds 2.
The board's decision not to consider the fourth bid is thought to have been
strongly opposed by the four directors who last year sought to unseat the
chairman at an extraordinary general meeting. It is likely the directors
will try to reconvene the egm, which was adjourned until no later than the
annual general meeting planned for this month.
All the bidders were seeking majority control although Berisford was
believed to be demanding at least 90 per cent. The investment consortium is
thought to be looking for at least 51 per cent.
The board faced three options in its choice of potential bidder: Berisford
has made no secret of its desire to build an international industrial
holding company spanning Europe and the US. Clark's would be just one of
four divisions, with the emphasis on making it more competitive in an
international environment.
FII, on the other hand, argues its knowledge of the shoe industry would
bring considerable benefit to both companies and few jobs would be lost. A
significant supplier to Marks and Spencer, FII would be able to introduce
Clark's range of children's and casual shoes to this market.
The investment consortium, meanwhile, is prepared to back the company's
existing management and is aiming for an eventual flotation.
</TEXT>
