<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Wilson Bowden declines 39% - Housebuilder
confirms revival in UK property market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WILSON BOWDEN yesterday reported a 50 per cent increase in agreed house
sales in the first 11 weeks of the year, confirming the revival in the UK
property market reported since the new year by estate agents, building
societies and other builders.
The increase follows a dreadful 12 months for the housing market; Wilson
Bowden yesterday announced a 39 per cent fall in pre-tax profits to Pounds
16.9m last year.
Since the new year net reservations, sales upon which a deposit has been
paid less cancellations, have risen by 50 per cent compared with the
corresponding period last year. Completed sales over the same period rose by
15 per cent.
Most encouraging was the fact that reservations, after dipping the week
before the Budget, rebounded back to previous high levels last weekend
following the Chancellor's statement.
The final dividend is held at 6.2p, making a maintained total for the year
of 8.7p. This was despite a 40 per cent fall in earnings per share to 14.6p
(24.5p).
The results, although disappointing, were better than many housebuilders
would be reporting for 1992, said Mr David Wilson, chairman and chief
executive. He said the company was well placed to take advantage of
increased sales.
Net debt of just Pounds 16.8m, compared with net cash of Pounds 7m 12 months
previously, meant that gearing was still only 10 per cent of shareholders
funds.
The group, therefore, did not need a rights issue to finance increased sales
but could purchase all the land it needed from its own resources and
borrowings. Gearing was expected to rise to no more than 20 per cent to 25
per cent this year.
During the past 14 months the group has increased the number of housing
sites it owns with planning permission from 7,900 plots to just under
10,000.
The share price rose 3p to 384p following the statement that the group
expected to build at least 20 per cent more homes this year.
Housebuilding profits fell by more than a third last year, from Pounds 21.5m
to Pounds 13.8m, despite a 3 per cent increase in the number of houses sold
to 1,367. Operating margins slipped from 20.3 per cent to 13.5 per cent,
reflecting pressure on house prices, the need to offer discounts to buyers
and other sales incentives as well as higher operating costs.
Commercial property profits fell from Pounds 6.7m to Pounds 4.4m as turnover
from property sales slipped from Pounds 30m to Pounds 25.2m.
Mr Wilson said that there was no sign of a pick up in the industrial and
commercial property market which he expected to lag the housing recovery by
at least 12 months
COMMENT
Following its rights issue two years ago, Wilson Bowden largely stayed out
of land buying in 1991. It made up for this last year, raising the number of
plots with planning permission by about a quarter as well as significantly
increasing the number of selling outlets. The timing looks to have been
perfect coinciding with a recovery in house sales. The decision to raise
gearing rather than equity is to be applauded and reflects the strength of
the balance sheet. Margins should increase as sales incentives, worth about
Pounds 2,500 to Pounds 3,000 a house, are eroded. Profits, given a fair
wind, could approach Pounds 20m this year putting the shares on a
prospective p/e of more than 20. A class act but one which, unfortunately
for stockholders, is already recognised in the share price.
</TEXT>
