<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Asarco renews Polish copper
overtures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ASARCO, THE North American integrated copper producer, has renewed efforts
to establish links with KGHM, the state-owned producer from Lubin, in South
Western Poland.
Yesterday Asarco together with Mitsui and Bechtel met with representatives
of KGHM in nearby Wroclaw to discuss proposals 'for the development of the
environment protection industry' in Poland, a cryptic communique stated.
KGHM last year paid 395bn zloty (USDollars 23.8m) in pollution fines and
would have paid a further Z344bn if the government had not reduced the
charges last autumn.
Last year Asarco proposed a management agreement to KGHM after exploring the
prospects for capital investment. However feeling against foreign investment
within KGHM continues to run high and Asarco have now withdrawn their
proposal. Western Mining of Australia has also shown interest in investing
in KGHM.
Last year the combine produced 387,000 tonnes of copper, 2.3 per cent more
than in 1991 despite a 32-day strike last summer. KGHM also produced 914
tonnes of silver last year. Net profits reached Z1,160bn of which Z606bn was
spent on capital investment.
