<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Business Law: Air crash verdict - Legal Briefs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A jury in Rochester, New York, has awarded Dollars 107.3m, the largest
verdict in aviation crash history, to the estate of a family of four who
died in a crash in North Carolina in November 1986. A jury found the
aircraft's engine manufacturer, Teledyne Continental Motors, negligent
because it had known about problems with the engine from correspondence with
the pilot.
Unusually for a verdict of this size, none of the award was for punitive
damages. The previous highest jury award for an air crash victim was Dollars
8m against Delta Airlines for the 1985 death of the head of IBM's personal
computer division and his wife.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Teledyne Continental Motors.
</CO>
<XX>
