<PROFILE>_AN-DCXAWAHIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930323
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / People: Bowing to Japanese wisdom
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Inchcape, the motor and business services group, has appointed a senior
Japanese executive, Hachiro Koyama, as non-executive chairman of the UK
company's Japanese subsidiary, Inchcape Dodwell.
Koyama, 70, is vice-president of the Nikkeiren employers' federation in
Japan and also representative director and chairman of SmithKline Beecham
there. He previously held executive positions with Standard Vacuum Oil,
Mobil Oil and Johnson Wax Japan.
Charles Mackay, Inchcape's chief executive, says the appointment of someone
of Koyama's stature underlines the importance of Japan to Inchcape, and the
group's efforts to develop a strong cadre of Japanese management.
The Tokyo-based subsidiary employs 2,000 people, nearly all of whom are
Japanese.
Inchcape's motors business in Japan consists of a new joint venture with
Peugeot to import and distribute the French group's cars, and a
Mercedes-Benz dealership in Tokyo. The UK group also represents nine
Japanese manufacturers, such as Toyota and Mazda, in world markets.
Inchcape's Japanese marketing businesses in Japan cover consumer goods,
industrial products and business machines, and its service businesses are
involved in shipping, insurance and testing.
In January Sir John Whitehead, former British ambassador to Japan, was
appointed to advise Inchcape's London board on Japanese affairs.
Inchcape has also announced the retirement of Peter Laister, 64, after
nearly 10 years as a non-executive director. A former chairman of Thorn-EMI
and the Maxwell Communication Corporation, Laister will now concentrate on
his other business interests, including the chairmanship of the Nimbus Group
of companies, which are involved in records, compact discs and CD-ROM
technology to store technical information.
</TEXT>
