<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Business Law: Challenge to legal basis for waste directive
rejected - European Law
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The European Court of Justice last week rejected a joint challenge by the
European Commission and the European Parliament to the legal basis chosen by
the Council for a directive on waste.
A proposal for the directive was first put forward by the Commission in
1988. The legal basis suggested by the Commission for the directive related
to the establishment and functioning of the single market. The Council
adopted the proposal but chose a different legal basis related specifically
to the protection of the environment.
At stake was the relative power of the Commission and the Parliament to
influence the final shape of the directive. Under the single market
legislative procedure the Commission and the Parliament have greater powers
of negotiation with the Council over the adoption of amendments than under
the environmental legislative procedure.
The Court said the choice of legal basis had to be based on objective
criteria capable of judicial control. The most important criteria were the
aims and content of the legislation in question.
It ruled that although there were certain elements in the directive which
impacted on the functioning of the single market - for instance the
introduction of a common definition of waste and related activities  - the
main aim and contents related to environmental protection. The legal basis
chosen by the Council was therefore correct.
The Parliament attempted to introduce a new ground for judicial review which
had not been raised by the Commission. The Court rejected it on the grounds
that an intervening party is limited to supporting the arguments put forward
by one of the main parties.
C-155/91: Commission (with the European Parliament intervening) v Council
(with Spain intervening), ECJ FC, 17 March 1993.
German rules on foreign seamen upheld.
The European Court has ruled that German rules which allow its merchant navy
to employ seamen from outside the Community who are neither domiciled nor
resident in Germany on less favourable terms than German seamen are not
contrary to the Rome treaty.
The case arose out of a dispute between a ship operator and its works
council. The ship operator wanted to employ a Filipino radio operator and
five other Filipino ratings. Under German law non-EC seamen can be employed
on ships flying the German flag without being subject to German law and in
particular without the necessity to pay the social security contributions
payable for German workers.
The dispute went before the national court at which point the works council
claimed the relevant German rules were contrary to Rome treaty provisions on
state aid and general social conditions.
The European Court said the national rules, effectively allowing Germany to
discriminate in favour of non-German seamen, were valid.
The rules did not constitute state aid. The Court rejected the Commission's
argument that they did because their aim - to make the German merchant navy
more competitive by granting advantages to it - clearly encapsulated all the
elements of state aid.
In order for a measure to come within the scope of the Rome treaty
provisions on state aid it was necessary to show that the advantages in
question arose directly from a grant by the state in question or through
resources of that state.
In relation to social conditions the court said implementation of the
objective of the rules was for the national authorities to determine.
Joined cases C-72/91 and C-73/91: Firma Sloman Neptun Schiffahrts AG v
Seebetriebsrat Bodo Ziesemer, ECJ FC, 17 March 1993.
Other cases
A company which has incurred loses due to administrative delays by an EC
state can rely on force majeure provisions in the relevant Community
legislation even though it has failed to take measures laid down in the
legislation to protect its position.
C-50/92: Firma Molkerie-Zentrale Sud GmbH &amp; Co KG v Bundesanstalt fur
landwirtschaftliche Marktordung ECJ 2 CH, 18 March 1993.
BRICK COURT CHAMBERS, BRUSSELS
</TEXT>
