<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Business Law: Crime and the City solution - The American
approach to tackling market misconduct may not work in the UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A central theme of the debate in the UK on reform of long fraud trials has
been whether more white-collar 'offences' should be taken out of the
criminal justice system and dealt with by City of London financial
regulators.
Advocates of making greater use of the administrative and regulatory regimes
for tackling market misconduct base their case on the apparent success that
the US has enjoyed in recent years with such an approach. However, research
published last week by the Royal Commission on Criminal Justice, chaired by
Lord Runciman, casts doubt on the benefits to be gained from adopting
similar methods in the UK.
The study, the first large-scale review of serious fraud since the 1986
Roskill Fraud Trials Report, concludes that there is considerable doubt in
the City and elsewhere about whether self-regulatory organisations would
have taken disciplinary action in recent high-profile cases, such as Blue
Arrow and Guinness, unless put under political pressure. The report
concedes, however, that there have been some cases, or parts of
prosecutions, which could have been dealt with outside the criminal justice
system.
The author of the report, Professor Michael Levi of Cardiff University, also
casts doubt on the notion that the US approach has been measurably better at
tackling white-collar crime than the UK system.
Allied to the suggestion that greater use should be made in the UK of
regulatory bodies when dealing with market 'offences' is the notion that the
UK has too many overlapping regulatory bodies and that some agency
equivalent to the US Securities and Exchange Commission is needed to reduce
inter-organisational rivalry, which may allow some white-collar 'offences'
to slip through the net.
Prof Levi points out, however, that the perceived superiority of the SEC
when it comes to dealing with market misconduct is largely because it is
underpinned by an extensive edifice of stock exchange and state securities
regulators.
Indeed, because most securities dealing is done under state jurisdiction
rather than federal, most official action in the US is taken by state
regulators, rather than by the SEC. In 1989, for example, the 1,258 state
personnel involved in regulation initiated a total of 3,678 enforcement
actions, including 335 criminal proceedings resulting in 253 convictions.
This compares with 310 actions taken by the SEC over the same period,
including less than a dozen criminal prosecutions initiated as a result of
SEC referral.
The reputation of the SEC was built in part on the spectacular junk-bond
insider-dealing prosecutions of Dennis Levine, Ivan Boesky and Michael
Milken in the late 1980s. But it should not be forgotten that for over two
years before these successes the SEC had made 20 failed attempts at
investigations into what turned out to be Levine's insider trades. It was an
anonymous letter from Venezuela to Merrill Lynch, via the firm passing the
file on to the SEC, that finally led to the successful prosecution of
Levine. This in turn triggered the wave of plea-bargaining with him and
Boesky which led eventually to Michael Milken.
The fact that the UK insider-dealing prosecutions have produced nothing of
an even remotely comparable status may be due to any number of reasons. It
may show that the UK system is badly designed, or that such offences are
inherently unprosecutable, or that no such important figures are involved in
Britain. But it is difficult to say that an SEC-style system in Britain
would have produced such spectacular results.
For many people the SEC's attraction lies in its ability to combine civil
and administrative remedies and the use of 'Wells submissions' - an informal
bargaining process between the SEC and the 'accused' designed to filter
cases which should not proceed to criminal prosecution.
The ability to freeze assets held in America and overseas and to fine
'offenders' vast sums - such as the Dollars 250m fine imposed on Salomon
Brothers for breach of the US Treasury bond auction rules (compare that with
the largest UK insider-dealing fine to date of Pounds 25,000) - certainly
has superficial attractions.
But the US system is not without its critics. The American Bar Association
has accused the SEC of using administrative actions as a way of evading
constitutional safeguards for the accused and winning cases which they could
not hope to prove to a criminal standard of proof. The failure of a number
of recent securities fraud prosecutions in the US suggests that courts and
juries are also beginning to react against the whole approach to tackling
market misconduct.
Prof Levi's point is that none of these facts or observations 'prove' the
superiority of the administrative/regulatory approach over the criminal
process or vice versa. If the UK was to move towards a regulatory approach
to market misconduct it would need to be sure that a number of conditions
would be met.
Regulators would have to be able to show that they are capable of working
more quickly, cheaply and fairly than the criminal courts. They would have
to show they could handle the sort of heavyweight cases such as Blue Arrow
that the SFO has been criticised by some people for prosecuting.
The government would also have to be sure that the sanctions available to
them were sufficient to satisfy the public that disciplinary action was not
a soft option and that the regulatory bodies had the political will to act
against leading corporate and professional figures.
Prof Levi says it is difficult to be confident of any of these things. In
particular he says it is hard to see which cases dealt with recently by
either the fraud investigation group of the Crown Prosecution Service or by
the Serious Fraud Office could plausibly have been dealt with by
disciplinary means, although some complex parts involving market practice
might usefully have been hived off.
Many securities cases involve theft of assets and it would be a very big
step to take them out of the courts. Even if people in the City agreed that
something was 'a regulatory breach rather than a crime for gain, the public
might not see it in quite the same light', he says.
These views are echoed by Mr George Staple, director of the SFO. Writing
recently in the Modern Law Review, Mr Staple asks whether it would be right
for someone alleged to have committed fraud to go before a self-regulatory
disciplinary tribunal which had no power to send him to prison and without
the public opprobrium which attaches to being found guilty in a criminal
court.
'Most people would take the view that the criminal justice system could not
possibly abdicate responsibility for dealing with serious criminal conduct
of this kind,' he said.
There is a further problem with placing greater emphasis on the regulatory
process - what to do with people such as Mr Roger Levitt, head of the
collapsed Levitt Group, and Mr Asil Nadir, former chairman of Polly Peck,
both of whom are due to stand trial in September and who are not required to
be members of any authorised body.
Clearly it would be wrong for the method of dealing with those accused of
white-collar offences to be determined by whether they belong to a
regulatory body.
The Royal Commission's views on long fraud trials will not be known until
the summer. But it already seems clear that the scope for taking more
white-collar offences out of the criminal justice system is limited.
</TEXT>
<XX>
